/* Country / territory descriptions (5-sentence, general & timeless — no number-grid figures) for the Atlas globe
   click popup. Regenerated from the accurate source summaries, adversarially fact-checked. Keyed by lowercased name.
   Load before app.js. Safe to re-generate. */
window.COUNTRY_INFO = {
  "accra": "Accra is the capital and largest city of Ghana, located on the country's southern coast along the Gulf of Guinea, an arm of the Atlantic Ocean. The name sometimes refers to the older, larger territory of the Accra Metropolitan District as it existed before its reorganization in 2008. That earlier district has since been divided into several local government districts. These include a number of independent municipal districts and a reduced Accra Metropolitan District. The Accra Metropolitan District is the only district within the capital area to hold formal city status.",
  "afghanistan": "Afghanistan is a landlocked country located at the crossroads of Central and South Asia. It is bordered by Pakistan to the east and south, Iran to the west, Turkmenistan to the northwest, Uzbekistan to the north, Tajikistan to the northeast, and China to the northeast and east. The country is predominantly mountainous, with plains in the north and the southwest that are separated by the Hindu Kush mountain range. Kabul is its capital and largest city. Its position at the crossroads of Central and South Asia has long made it a meeting point of the two regions.",
  "akrotiri": "Akrotiri is a Greek place name meaning \"cape\" or \"promontory.\" Because of this general meaning, the name is shared by many different seaside locations. It is derived from the Greek word for a headland jutting into the sea. As a common toponym, it appears across Greek-speaking coastal regions. The name accordingly refers to several distinct capes and settlements rather than a single place.",
  "albania": "Albania is a country in Southeast Europe, situated in the Balkans along the Adriatic and Ionian Seas within the Mediterranean. It shares land borders with Montenegro to the northwest, Kosovo to the northeast, North Macedonia to the east, and Greece to the south. Its terrain is highly varied, ranging from rugged, snow-capped ranges such as the Albanian Alps and the Korab, Skanderbeg, Pindus, and Ceraunian Mountains to fertile lowland plains along the coasts. The country encompasses a wide range of climatic, geological, and hydrological conditions across its compact territory. Tirana is the capital and largest city, followed by Durrës, Vlorë, and Shkodër.",
  "algeria": "Algeria is a country in the Maghreb region of North Africa and is the largest country on the African continent by land area. It is bordered to the northeast by Tunisia, to the east by Libya, to the southeast by Niger, to the southwest by Mali, Mauritania, and Western Sahara, to the west by Morocco, and to the north by the Mediterranean Sea. It is also the tenth-largest country in the world. Algiers is its capital and largest city. It ranks among the most populous countries in Africa.",
  "american samoa": "American Samoa is a self-governing, unincorporated territory of the United States located in the south Pacific Ocean, within the Polynesia subregion of Oceania. It lies southeast of the independent nation of Samoa, east of the International Date Line, and near neighbors including Wallis and Futuna, the Cook Islands, Tonga, and Tokelau. It is the southernmost territory of the United States, situated far to the southwest of the U.S. state of Hawaii. It is one of only two U.S. territories located south of the Equator, along with the uninhabited Jarvis Island. Its distinctive position places it among the most remote parts of the United States.",
  "andorra": "Andorra is a landlocked country on the Iberian Peninsula, set high in the eastern Pyrenees of southwestern Europe and bordered by France to the north and Spain to the south. It is traditionally believed to have been created by Charlemagne and was later ruled by the count of Urgell before being transferred to the Diocese of Urgell in 988. The country was formed as a polity by a charter in 1278, remaining a lordship within the Principality of Catalonia until 1715. It is governed as a principality headed by two co-princes: the Bishop of Urgell in Spain and the president of France. Its capital and largest city is Andorra la Vella.",
  "angola": "Angola is a country on the western coast of Southern Africa and one of the largest nations on the continent. A Portuguese-speaking state, it shares that colonial linguistic heritage with several other Lusophone countries. It is bordered by Namibia to the south, the Democratic Republic of the Congo to the north, Zambia to the east, and the Atlantic Ocean to the west. Angola includes an exclave province, Cabinda, which borders the Republic of the Congo and the Democratic Republic of the Congo. Its capital and most populous city is Luanda.",
  "anguilla": "Anguilla is a British Overseas Territory in the Caribbean, situated in the North Atlantic Ocean. It is one of the most northerly of the Leeward Islands in the Lesser Antilles, lying east of Puerto Rico and the Virgin Islands and directly north of Saint Martin. The territory consists of the main island of Anguilla, a long and narrow low-lying island, together with a number of much smaller uninhabited islands and cays. Its capital is The Valley. As a British Overseas Territory, it remains under British sovereignty while managing its own local affairs.",
  "antarctica": "Antarctica is Earth's southernmost and least-populated continent. Situated almost entirely south of the Antarctic Circle and surrounded by the Southern Ocean, it contains the geographic South Pole. Most of its surface is covered by the vast Antarctic ice sheet, which reaches great average thickness. On average, it is the coldest, driest, and windiest of the continents and has the highest average elevation. As the least-populated continent, it has no permanent inhabitants.",
  "antigua and barb.": "Antigua and Barbuda is an archipelagic country in the Caribbean composed of Antigua, Barbuda, and dozens of other small islands. It is one of the smallest countries in the Caribbean by land area. The terrain is mostly flat, with the highest points found in the Shekerley Mountains on Antigua and the Highlands on Barbuda. The islands have a tropical savanna climate, with pockets of tropical monsoon in Antigua's southwest. Its most populated city is St. John's, followed by All Saints and Bolans.",
  "antigua and barbuda": "Antigua and Barbuda is an archipelagic country in the Caribbean composed of Antigua, Barbuda, and dozens of other small islands. It is one of the smallest countries in the Caribbean by land area. The terrain is mostly flat, with the highest points found in the Shekerley Mountains on Antigua and the Highlands on Barbuda. The islands have a tropical savanna climate, with pockets of tropical monsoon in Antigua's southwest. Its most populated city is St. John's, followed by All Saints and Bolans.",
  "arabia": "The Arabian Peninsula, or simply Arabia, is a peninsula in West Asia that forms most of the land on the Arabian tectonic plate. It is the world's largest peninsula, roughly comparable in size to India. Nine countries lie wholly or partly on the peninsula, including Bahrain, Kuwait, Oman, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, and Yemen. The southern portions of Iraq and Jordan also extend onto it. It accounts for the majority of the land situated on the Arabian plate.",
  "argentina": "Argentina is a country in the Southern Cone of South America and the second-largest country on the continent after Brazil. It shares the bulk of the Southern Cone with Chile to the west and is also bordered by Bolivia and Paraguay to the north, Brazil to the northeast, Uruguay and the South Atlantic Ocean to the east, and the Drake Passage to the south. It is a federal state subdivided into twenty-three provinces and one autonomous city, Buenos Aires, which serves as the federal capital and largest city. The provinces and the capital have their own constitutions while existing within a shared federal system. It is the second-largest country in South America and the eighth-largest in the world.",
  "armenia": "Armenia is a landlocked country in the Armenian highlands of West Asia, forming part of the wider Caucasus region. It is bordered by Turkey to the west, Georgia to the north, Azerbaijan to the east, and Iran and the Azerbaijani exclave of Nakhchivan to the south. Yerevan serves as its capital, largest city, and financial center. The Armenian highlands were historically home to peoples such as the Hayasa-Azzi, Shupria, and Nairi. By at least 600 BC an archaic form of Proto-Armenian, an Indo-European language, had diffused into the region.",
  "aruba": "Aruba is a constituent island country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands, lying in the southern Caribbean Sea. It sits a short distance north of the Venezuelan peninsula of Paraguaná and northwest of Curaçao. In 1986 it became a constituent country within the Kingdom and acquired its present official name. The island stretches from its northwestern to its southeastern end and narrows to a modest width at its broadest point. Geologically it belongs to South America, resting on the South American continental shelf.",
  "asante": "The Asante (also spelled Ashanti) Empire was an Akan state in the forest region of what is now south-central Ghana, together with adjoining parts of present-day Côte d'Ivoire and Togo. Founded around the turn of the eighteenth century under Osei Tutu and his adviser Okomfo Anokye, it united a confederation of Akan chiefdoms centered on the capital, Kumasi. Its ruler bore the title Asantehene, and the sacred Golden Stool (Sika Dwa) served as the spiritual embodiment of the nation and the symbol of the king's authority. The empire grew into one of West Africa's most powerful states, sustained by gold, trade, and a sophisticated administration, and it fought a long series of wars against the British from the early nineteenth century onward. Following its defeat in these conflicts, Asante was annexed by Britain in the early twentieth century and absorbed into the Gold Coast, though the Asante monarchy and its traditions endured.",
  "ashmore and cartier is.": "The Territory of Ashmore and Cartier Islands is an uninhabited external territory of Australia made up of four low-lying islands across two separate reefs. It lies in the Timor Sea on the edge of the Sahul Shelf, off the northwest coast of Australia and south of the Indonesian island of Rote. The islands were reached by Indonesian fishermen in the early 1700s, who visited regularly to harvest sea cucumbers. Cartier Reef and Ashmore Reef were charted by Europeans around 1800 and 1811 respectively. In the late nineteenth century they were mined for guano by American whalers.",
  "australia": "Australia is a country comprising the mainland of the Australian continent, the island of Tasmania, and numerous smaller islands. It ranks among the largest countries in the world and is the flattest and driest inhabited continent. As a megadiverse land, its vast expanse encompasses a wide variety of landscapes and climates, from deserts in the interior to tropical rainforests along the coast. The ancestors of Aboriginal Australians began arriving from Southeast Asia tens of thousands of years ago, during the Last Glacial Period. Their arrival marks the beginning of a deep Indigenous presence across the continent.",
  "austria": "Austria is a landlocked country in Central Europe, lying in the Eastern Alps. It is organized as a federation of nine states, of which the capital Vienna is the most populous city and also a state in its own right. Austria is bordered by Germany, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Hungary, Slovenia, Italy, Switzerland, and Liechtenstein. The area of today's Austria has been inhabited since at least the Paleolithic period. Its position in the Eastern Alps gives much of the country a mountainous character.",
  "austria hungary": "Austria-Hungary, also known as the Austro-Hungarian Empire, was a multi-national constitutional dual monarchy in Central Europe that existed between 1867 and 1918. It joined two sovereign states under a single ruler titled both Emperor of Austria and Apostolic King of Hungary. The union represented the last phase in the constitutional evolution of the Habsburg monarchy. It was formed by the Austro-Hungarian Compromise of 1867, in the aftermath of the Austro-Prussian War. The arrangement followed earlier Hungarian struggles for independence, including Rákóczi's War of Independence and the Hungarian Revolution of 1848–1849, waged in opposition to Habsburg rule.",
  "azerbaijan": "Azerbaijan is a transcontinental landlocked country at the boundary of Western Asia and Eastern Europe, forming part of the South Caucasus region. It is bounded by the Caspian Sea to the east, Russia's republic of Dagestan to the north, Georgia to the northwest, Turkey and Armenia to the west, and Iran to the south, with the exclave of Nakhchivan set apart from the main territory. Baku is its capital and largest city. In antiquity the territory was ruled first by Caucasian Albania. It later came under the control of various Persian empires.",
  "bahamas": "The Bahamas is an archipelagic country in the Caribbean, situated within the Lucayan Archipelago in the Atlantic Ocean. It comprises hundreds of islands and thousands of cays lying north of Cuba, northwest of Hispaniola and the Turks and Caicos Islands, and southeast of Florida. Its capital and largest city is Nassau on the island of New Providence. The nation's territory spreads across a vast expanse of ocean space dotted with low-lying islands. For many centuries the islands were inhabited by the Arawak and Lucayans, a branch of the Arawakan-speaking Taíno.",
  "bahrain": "Bahrain is an island country in West Asia, situated near the western shore of the Persian Gulf. It consists of a small archipelago of natural and artificial islands centered on Bahrain Island, which makes up the great majority of its landmass. The country lies between Qatar and the northeastern coast of Saudi Arabia, to which it is connected by the King Fahd Causeway. Its population includes both Bahraini nationals and a large community of expatriates. Compact in size, it is among the smallest nations in Asia.",
  "baikonur": "Baikonur is a city in Kazakhstan on the northern bank of the Syr Darya river. It is leased and administered by the Russian Federation under a long-term arrangement. The town was built to serve the nearby Baikonur Cosmodrome, providing administrative offices and housing for its employees. During the Soviet period it was known as Leninsk and was sometimes referred to as Zvezdograd, meaning 'Star City'. It was officially renamed Baikonur by Russian president Boris Yeltsin on December 20, 1995.",
  "bajo nuevo bank": "Bajo Nuevo Bank, also known as the Petrel Islands, is an uninhabited reef with a few grass-covered islets in the western Caribbean Sea. Its nearest neighboring land feature is Serranilla Bank, lying some distance to the west. The reef is the subject of a sovereignty dispute involving Colombia, Jamaica, and the United States. In 2012 the International Court of Justice addressed Nicaraguan claims to the area. It ruled that Colombia held sovereignty over both Bajo Nuevo and Serranilla Banks.",
  "bangladesh": "Bangladesh is a country in South Asia, ranking among the most populous and most densely populated nations in the world. It shares land borders with India to the north, west, and east, and with Myanmar to the southeast. To its south lies a coastline along the Bay of Bengal, while the narrow Siliguri Corridor separates it from Bhutan and Nepal, and the Indian state of Sikkim divides it from China to the north. Dhaka, its capital and largest city, is the nation's political, financial, and cultural centre. Its location on the Bay of Bengal gives it a coastline along the country's southern edge.",
  "barbados": "Barbados is an island nation in the Caribbean, lying in the Atlantic Ocean. It forms part of the Lesser Antilles of the West Indies and is the southernmost and easternmost island of the Caribbean region. It sits on the boundary of the South American and Caribbean tectonic plates. Its capital and largest city is Bridgetown. The island was inhabited by the Kalinago people from the 13th century, and by other Indigenous peoples before them, who knew it as Ichirouganaim.",
  "barotse": "Barotseland, called Bulozi or Barotseland by its people, is the homeland of the Lozi, a Bantu-speaking ethnic group also known as the Balozi. The Lozi are native to the region straddling parts of present-day Zambia and Zimbabwe. They are not a single tribe but a confederation encompassing many groups, among them the Bamakoma, Kwanda, Lukolwe, Bafwe, Batotela, Bayeyi, Mbowe, Bambukushu, Muenyi, Mwanga and Basubia. Intermarriage among these tribes has long reinforced their shared cultural identity. The name thus denotes both a people and the territory they regard as their own.",
  "basutoland": "Basutoland was a British Crown colony in Southern Africa occupying the territory of present-day Lesotho. Its people, the Basotho, and their land came under British control in 1868 and were ruled by the Cape Colony from 1871, an arrangement that proved unpopular and ineffective at governing the territory. As a result it was placed under the direct authority of the British Crown, administered through a High Commissioner and a series of Resident Commissioners presiding over an Executive Council. Bordered by the Cape, Natal and Orange River colonies and later entirely surrounded by South Africa, it remained a distinct enclave. It was divided into the districts of Berea, Leribe, Maseru, Mohale's Hoek, Mafeteng, Qacha's Nek and Quthing.",
  "belarus": "Belarus, officially the Republic of Belarus, is a landlocked country in Eastern Europe. It is bordered by Russia to the east and northeast, Ukraine to the south, Poland to the west, and Lithuania and Latvia to the northwest. The country has a hemiboreal climate. It is administratively divided into six regions. Minsk is the capital and largest city, administered separately as a city with special status.",
  "belgium": "Belgium, officially the Kingdom of Belgium, is a country in Northwestern Europe within the coastal lowland region known as the Low Countries. It is bordered by the Netherlands to the north, Germany to the east, Luxembourg to the southeast, France to the south, and the North Sea to the west. The capital and largest metropolitan region is Brussels, while other major cities include Antwerp, Ghent, Charleroi, Liège, Bruges, Namur, and Leuven. Belgium is a parliamentary constitutional monarchy with a complex federal system structured along regional and linguistic lines. It is one of Europe's most densely populated states.",
  "belize": "Belize is a country on the northeastern coast of Central America. It is bordered by Mexico to the north, the Caribbean Sea to the east, and Guatemala to the west and south, and shares a maritime boundary with Honduras to the southeast. Part of the Caribbean region, it is a member of the Caribbean Community and the Commonwealth Caribbean, the historical British West Indies. The Maya civilization spread into the area between about 1500 BC and 300 AD and flourished there until around 1200. This heritage, alongside later British colonial influence, shapes Belize's distinctive cultural character.",
  "benin": "Benin, officially the Republic of Benin and formerly known as Dahomey, is a country in West Africa. It is bordered by Togo to the west, Nigeria to the east, Burkina Faso to the northwest, and Niger to the northeast. Much of its population lives along the southern coastline of the Bight of Benin, part of the Gulf of Guinea on the northernmost tropical edge of the Atlantic Ocean. The official capital is Porto-Novo, while the seat of government lies in Cotonou, the most populous city and economic center. Together these give the country both an administrative and an economic focal point along its southern coast.",
  "bermuda": "Bermuda is a British Overseas Territory in the North Atlantic Ocean. The nearest land is the US state of North Carolina, roughly 1,035 kilometres to the west-northwest. It is an archipelago of some 181 islands, the most significant of which are linked by bridges so that they appear to form a single landmass. The territory has a tropical climate marked by warm winters and hot summers. Its position in the open North Atlantic leaves it far removed from any other land.",
  "bhutan": "Bhutan, officially the Kingdom of Bhutan, is a landlocked country in South Asia located in the Eastern Himalayas. It borders China to the north and northwest and India to the south and southeast. It is a constitutional monarchy in which a King serves as head of state and a prime minister as head of government. The Je Khenpo is the head of the state religion, Vajrayana Buddhism, which is central to Bhutanese culture. The Himalayan mountains in the north rise sharply from the country's lush subtropical plains in the south.",
  "bir tawil": "Bir Tawil, whose name means 'tall water well,' is an area of land along the border between Egypt and Sudan that is claimed by neither country. Together with the neighbouring Halaib Triangle it is sometimes called the Bir Tawil Triangle, despite its quadrilateral shape, the two regions meeting at a quadripoint. Its unclaimed status arises from a discrepancy between the straight political boundary set between Egypt and Sudan in 1899 and the irregular administrative boundary set in 1902. Egypt asserts the political boundary while Sudan asserts the administrative one, so that the Halaib Triangle is claimed by both and Bir Tawil by neither. This makes it one of the few land areas on Earth actively renounced by all bordering states.",
  "bolivia": "Bolivia, officially the Plurinational State of Bolivia, is a landlocked country in central South America. Its geography is dominated by an Andean region to the west, including the high-altitude Altiplano plateau, snow-capped peaks and temperate valleys, and by tropical lowlands to the east and north. This range produces a wide diversity of climates and biomes, from the vast Amazonian plain and the Gran Chaco to part of the Pantanal, the world's largest tropical wetland, along its eastern border. Bolivia is bordered by Brazil to the north and east, Paraguay to the southeast, Argentina to the south, Chile to the southwest, and Peru to the west. Its landlocked position and varied terrain have strongly shaped its history and identity.",
  "bosnia and herz.": "Bosnia and Herzegovina, often called Bosnia-Herzegovina or simply Bosnia, is a country in Southeast Europe on the Balkan Peninsula. It borders Serbia to the east, Montenegro to the southeast, and Croatia to the north and southwest, with a short coast on the Adriatic Sea in the south. Bosnia, the larger northern region, has a moderate continental climate with hot summers and cold, snowy winters. Its geography is largely mountainous, especially in the central and eastern parts dominated by the Dinaric Alps. Herzegovina, the smaller southern region, has a Mediterranean climate and is likewise mostly mountainous.",
  "bosnia-herzegovina": "Bosnia and Herzegovina, often called Bosnia-Herzegovina or simply Bosnia, is a country in Southeast Europe on the Balkan Peninsula. It borders Serbia to the east, Montenegro to the southeast, and Croatia to the north and southwest, with a short coast on the Adriatic Sea in the south. Bosnia, the larger northern region, has a moderate continental climate with hot summers and cold, snowy winters. Its geography is largely mountainous, especially in the central and eastern parts dominated by the Dinaric Alps. Herzegovina, the smaller southern region, has a Mediterranean climate and is likewise mostly mountainous.",
  "botswana": "Botswana, officially the Republic of Botswana, is a landlocked country in Southern Africa. It is topographically flat, with roughly seventy percent of its territory forming part of the Kalahari Desert. It is bordered by South Africa to the south and southeast, Namibia to the west and north, Zambia to the north, and Zimbabwe to the northeast. Sparsely populated relative to its size, it is de facto the nation-state of the Batswana people, who make up the large majority of the population. The Kalanga people form the single largest ethnic minority.",
  "br. indian ocean ter.": "The British Indian Ocean Territory is a British Overseas Territory situated in the Indian Ocean. It comprises the seven atolls of the Chagos Archipelago, made up of more than a thousand individual islands, many of them very small. The largest and most southerly island is Diego Garcia, the site of a joint military facility of the United Kingdom and the United States. Official administration is conducted remotely from London, though the local capital is often regarded as being on Diego Garcia. Mauritius contests British control, arguing that the government separated the Chagos Archipelago from Mauritius to create the territory as a new colony.",
  "brazil": "Brazil, officially the Federative Republic of Brazil, is the largest country in South America and one of the largest in the world by both area and population. It is a federation composed of twenty-six states and a Federal District, which hosts the capital, Brasília. Its most populous city is São Paulo, followed by Rio de Janeiro. Brazil has more Portuguese speakers than any other country and is the only nation in the Americas where Portuguese is an official language. This Portuguese heritage, rooted in the colonial era, sets Brazil apart culturally and linguistically from its Spanish-speaking neighbours.",
  "british guiana": "British Guiana was a British colony on the northern coast of South America. Since 1966 the territory has existed as the independent nation of Guyana. Among the first known Europeans to encounter the wider Guiana region were the English explorer Sir Walter Raleigh and his crew, and Raleigh later published a book titled The Discovery of Guiana, though it dealt mainly with the Guayana region of present-day Venezuela. The Dutch were the first Europeans to settle in the area, beginning in the early seventeenth century. Control later passed to Britain, giving the colony its name and its lasting English-speaking and Caribbean character.",
  "british raj": "The British Raj was the period of rule by the British Crown over the Indian subcontinent, lasting from 1858 to 1947. It is also known as Crown rule or direct rule in India, and the region was commonly called India in contemporary usage. It included areas directly administered by the United Kingdom, collectively called British India, and areas ruled by indigenous rulers under British paramountcy, known as the princely states. The region was sometimes informally called the Indian Empire, though this was never an official title. As India, it was a founding member of the League of Nations and of the United Nations in 1945.",
  "british virgin is.": "The British Virgin Islands, officially the Virgin Islands, are a British Overseas Territory in the Caribbean, lying east of Puerto Rico and the US Virgin Islands and north-west of Anguilla. They are geographically part of the Virgin Islands archipelago, within the Leeward Islands of the Lesser Antilles and the broader West Indies. The territory consists of the main islands of Tortola, Virgin Gorda, Anegada and Jost Van Dyke, along with more than fifty smaller islands and cays, of which about sixteen are inhabited. The capital, Road Town, sits on Tortola, the largest island. Its Caribbean setting and status as a British possession shape its enduring identity.",
  "brunei": "Brunei, officially Brunei Darussalam, is a country in Southeast Asia on the northern coast of the island of Borneo. Apart from its coastline on the South China Sea, it is completely surrounded by the Malaysian state of Sarawak, whose Limbang district splits Brunei's territory into two parts. It is the only sovereign state located entirely on Borneo, the rest of the island being divided between Malaysia and Indonesia. Its capital and largest city is Bandar Seri Begawan. Malay is the official language, and Sunni Islam is the state religion, though other faiths are nominally tolerated.",
  "buganda": "Buganda is a Bantu kingdom within Uganda and the homeland of the Baganda people. It is the largest of the traditional kingdoms in present-day East Africa, encompassing Uganda's Central Region, including the national capital Kampala. The Baganda form the largest ethnic group in Uganda and a significant share of its population. The kingdom traces its unification to the thirteenth century under its first king, Kato Kintu, founder of the Kintu dynasty. Buganda grew into one of the largest and most powerful states in East Africa during the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries.",
  "bulgaria": "Bulgaria, officially the Republic of Bulgaria, is a country in Southeast Europe on the eastern part of the Balkan Peninsula. It lies directly south of the Danube river and west of the Black Sea. Bulgaria is bordered by Greece and Turkey to the south, Serbia and North Macedonia to the west, and Romania across the Danube to the north. Sofia is the nation's capital and largest city, with other major cities including Plovdiv, Varna, and Burgas. Its position on the Balkans has made it a historic crossroads between Europe and the Near East.",
  "bunyoro": "Bunyoro, also called Bunyoro-Kitara, is a traditional Bantu kingdom in Western Uganda. It was one of the most powerful kingdoms in Central and East Africa from the sixteenth to the nineteenth century. The kingdom is ruled by a monarch bearing the title Omukama of Bunyoro-Kitara. Its rulers have long held both political and cultural authority over the Banyoro people. The kingdom's historical strength and enduring dynastic tradition remain central to its identity.",
  "burkina faso": "Burkina Faso is a landlocked country in West Africa. It is bordered by Mali to the northwest, Niger to the northeast, Benin to the southeast, Togo and Ghana to the south, and Ivory Coast to the southwest. It shares its longest frontiers with these neighbours across the interior of the region. After gaining independence, it was known as the Republic of Upper Volta from 1958 to 1984 before adopting its present name. The change of name reflected a break from the colonial-era designation toward a national identity.",
  "burundi": "Burundi, officially the Republic of Burundi, is a landlocked country in East Africa. It lies in the Great Rift Valley at the junction between the African Great Lakes region and Southeast Africa. It is bordered by Rwanda to the north, Tanzania to the east and southeast, and the Democratic Republic of the Congo to the west, with Lake Tanganyika running along its southwestern edge. Gitega is the political capital, while Bujumbura is the economic capital and largest city. The Twa, Hutu, and Tutsi peoples have lived in the territory for at least five hundred years.",
  "cabo verde": "Cabo Verde, also known in English as Cape Verde and officially the Republic of Cabo Verde, is an archipelagic country in the central Atlantic Ocean off the coast of West Africa. It consists of ten volcanic islands lying several hundred kilometres west of Cap-Vert, the westernmost point of continental Africa, after which the islands are named. The country forms part of the Macaronesia ecoregion, along with the Azores, the Canary Islands, Madeira and the Savage Isles. Its Portuguese colonial heritage is reflected in its official language and its Cape Verdean Creole. The islands' Atlantic location has long made them a crossroads of oceanic trade and migration.",
  "calabar": "Calabar is the capital city of Cross River State in southeastern Nigeria. It was originally named Akwa Akpa in the Efik language, as the Efik people have historically dominated the area. The city sits adjacent to the Calabar and Great Kwa rivers and the creeks of the Cross River inland delta. Calabar has been described as a tourism capital of Nigeria, gaining a reputation as one of the country's cleanest and most environmentally friendly cities. Its riverine setting and Efik heritage give it a distinctive place among Nigerian cities.",
  "cambodia": "Cambodia, officially the Kingdom of Cambodia, is a country in mainland Southeast Asia. It is bordered by Thailand to the northwest, Laos to the north, and Vietnam to the east, with a coastline along the Gulf of Thailand to the southwest. Its landscape is dominated by a low-lying plain and the confluence of the Mekong river and the Tonlé Sap, Southeast Asia's largest lake. The country has a tropical climate. Its population is predominantly ethnically Khmer, whose culture and language define the nation's heritage.",
  "cameroon": "Cameroon, officially the Republic of Cameroon, is a country in Central Africa. It shares borders with Nigeria to the west and north, Chad to the northeast, the Central African Republic to the east, and Equatorial Guinea, Gabon, and the Republic of the Congo to the south. Its coastline lies on the Bight of Biafra, part of the Gulf of Guinea and the Atlantic Ocean. Because of its position at the crossroads between West Africa and Central Africa, it is often described as belonging to both regions. Cameroon is notably diverse, with hundreds of native languages spoken alongside its national languages, English and French.",
  "canada": "Canada is a country in North America whose ten provinces and three territories stretch from the Atlantic Ocean to the Pacific Ocean and northward into the Arctic Ocean. It is the second-largest country in the world by total area and has the longest coastline of any nation. Its boundary with the United States is the longest international land border on Earth. The country is characterized by a wide range of both meteorological and geological regions. Population densities vary greatly, with most people living in urban areas and vast stretches remaining sparsely inhabited.",
  "cape colony": "The Cape Colony, also known as the Cape of Good Hope, was a British colony in present-day South Africa named after the Cape of Good Hope. It began as a Dutch colony established in 1652 by the Dutch East India Company, which governed it from 1652 to 1795. The British took control in 1795, and after a period of Batavian rule from 1803 to 1806, held it again from 1806 until 1910. In 1910 it united with three other colonies to form the Union of South Africa and thereafter became the Cape Province. The Cape Province continued to exist even after 1961, when South Africa became a republic.",
  "cayman is.": "The Cayman Islands are a self-governing British Overseas Territory in the western Caribbean. The territory comprises the three islands of Grand Cayman, Cayman Brac, and Little Cayman, which lie south of Cuba and north-east of Honduras, between Jamaica and Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula. The capital city is George Town, on Grand Cayman, which is the most populous of the three islands. The Cayman Islands are considered to be part of the geographic Western Caribbean zone as well as the Greater Antilles. It is the most populated of all the British Overseas Territories.",
  "central african rep.": "The Central African Republic is a landlocked country located in Central Africa. It is bordered by Chad to the north, Sudan to the northeast, South Sudan to the east, the Democratic Republic of the Congo to the south, the Republic of the Congo to the southwest, and Cameroon to the west. Its population consists of about 80 ethnic groups. It was formerly a French colony known as Ubangi-Shari, and French remains its official language. Sango, a Ngbandi-based creole language, serves as the national and co-official language.",
  "ceylon": "Ceylon is the former name of Sri Lanka, an island country in South Asia. It is located in the Indian Ocean, southwest of the Bay of Bengal, and is separated from India by the Gulf of Mannar and the Palk Strait. It shares a maritime border with the Maldives to the southwest and India to the northwest, and lies across the Bay of Bengal from Bangladesh and Myanmar to the northeast. Its capital is Sri Jayawardenepura Kotte, while Colombo is its largest city and the political, financial, and cultural centre. It is separated from the Andaman and Nicobar Islands of India, which lie to its east.",
  "chad": "Chad, officially the Republic of Chad, is a country in Central Africa. It is bordered by Libya to the north, Sudan to the east, the Central African Republic to the south, Cameroon and Nigeria to the southwest, and Niger to the west. Its capital and largest city is N'Djamena, and it borders Nigeria at Lake Chad. It is the fifth-largest country in Africa and the twentieth largest nation by area. Chad's official languages are French and Arabic, with French serving as the lingua franca and the language of government and education.",
  "chile": "Chile, officially the Republic of Chile, is a country in western South America. It is the southernmost country in the world and the closest to Antarctica, extending along a narrow strip of land between the Andes Mountains and the Pacific Ocean. It shares borders with Peru to the north, Bolivia to the northeast, and Argentina to the east, with the Drake Passage lying to the south. Chile also administers several Pacific islands, including the Juan Fernández archipelago, Isla Salas y Gómez, the Desventuradas Islands, and Easter Island. It further claims a wedge of Antarctica as the Chilean Antarctic Territory.",
  "china": "China, officially the People's Republic of China, is a country in East Asia and one of the most populous nations in the world. It is divided into province-level divisions, including special administrative regions, with Beijing as its capital and Shanghai as its most populous urban area. Its geography features the vast Central Plain, deserts, subtropical and temperate forests, and towering mountain ranges such as the Himalayas. Major rivers including the Yangtze and the Yellow River flow across its landscape and have long shaped its settlement and agriculture. It ranks among the largest countries by land area and possesses a wide diversity of climates and terrains.",
  "clipperton i.": "Clipperton Island, also known as Clipperton Atoll, is an uninhabited coral atoll in the eastern Pacific Ocean. It is the only French territory in the North Pacific, lying far from the French mainland and from French Polynesia, and closest to the Mexican port of Acapulco. The island was documented by French merchant-explorers in 1711 and formally claimed as part of the French protectorate of Tahiti in 1858. American guano miners nonetheless began working the island in the early 1890s, contesting its control. A remote ring of coral enclosing a lagoon, it remains without permanent inhabitants.",
  "colombia": "Colombia, officially the Republic of Colombia, is a country in South America, with insular regions in North America. Its mainland is bordered by the Caribbean Sea to the north, Venezuela to the east, Brazil to the southeast, Peru and Ecuador to the south and southwest, the Pacific Ocean to the west, and Panama to the northwest. The country is divided into departments, with the Capital District of Bogota as its largest city and its principal financial and cultural hub. Other major urban centres include Medellin, Cali, Barranquilla, Cartagena, and Bucaramanga. Further urban areas include Pereira, Santa Marta, Cucuta, Ibague, Villavicencio, and Manizales.",
  "comoros": "The Comoros, officially the Union of the Comoros, is an archipelagic country made up of three islands off the coast of Southeast Africa. It lies at the northern end of the Mozambique Channel in the Indian Ocean, with Moroni as its capital and largest city. Islam is the predominant religion of the population and the official state religion. The country proclaimed its independence from France in 1975. It has three official languages: Comorian, French, and Arabic.",
  "congo": "The Republic of the Congo, commonly called Congo-Brazzaville after its capital, is a country on the western coast of Central Africa, lying to the west of the lower Congo River. It borders Gabon, Cameroon, the Central African Republic, the Democratic Republic of the Congo, the Angolan exclave of Cabinda, and the Atlantic Ocean. The region was long home to Bantu-speaking peoples and precolonial states such as the Kingdom of Loango and the Tio (Teke) Kingdom before France colonized it in the late nineteenth century and administered it as the Middle Congo within French Equatorial Africa. It became independent from France in August 1960, and its politics have since been shaped by periods of Marxist-Leninist single-party rule, civil conflict, and the long dominance of President Denis Sassou Nguesso. Its economy is heavily dependent on petroleum, and it should not be confused with the larger neighboring Democratic Republic of the Congo across the river.",
  "cook is.": "The Cook Islands are an island country and associated state of New Zealand in Polynesia, part of Oceania, in the South Pacific Ocean. The country consists of fifteen islands scattered across a large expanse of ocean. The capital is Avarua, located on the island of Rarotonga. The Cook Islands are self-governing while in free association with New Zealand. Their exclusive economic zone covers a vast area of the surrounding ocean.",
  "coral sea is.": "The Coral Sea Islands Territory is an external territory of Australia lying in the Coral Sea, north-east of Queensland. It encompasses a large area of ocean scattered with small islands and reefs, though their combined land area is very small. Apart from a small staff of Bureau of Meteorology employees at a weather station on Willis Island, the territory is uninhabited. The islands and reefs were charted in the early 1800s, and some were briefly mined for guano between the 1870s and 1880s. A weather monitoring station was established on Willis Island in 1921 and remains its main human presence.",
  "costa rica": "Costa Rica, officially the Republic of Costa Rica, is a country in Central America. It borders Nicaragua to the north, the Caribbean Sea to the northeast, Panama to the southeast, and the Pacific Ocean to the southwest, and shares a maritime border with Ecuador to the south of Cocos Island. Its capital and largest city is San José, which anchors a surrounding metropolitan area. Humans have been present in the region since between roughly 7,000 and 10,000 BC. Various indigenous peoples inhabited the territory before it was colonized by Spain in the 16th century.",
  "cotonou": "Cotonou is the largest city and seat of government of Benin. It lies in the southeast of the country, between the Atlantic Ocean and Lake Nokoué. It serves as the administrative heart of the republic, home to most government buildings, government departments, and foreign embassies. The official capital, where the national legislature sits, is the smaller city of Porto-Novo. The urban area continues to expand, notably toward the west.",
  "croatia": "Croatia, officially the Republic of Croatia, is a country in Central and Southeast Europe, on the coast of the Adriatic Sea. It borders Slovenia to the northwest, Hungary to the northeast, Serbia to the east, Bosnia and Herzegovina and Montenegro to the southeast, and shares a maritime border with Italy to the west. The Croatian archipelago contains over 1,000 islands and islets, the largest such territory on the Adriatic. Its capital, largest city, and main cultural and economic centre is Zagreb. Other major urban centres include Split, Rijeka, and Osijek.",
  "cuba": "Cuba, officially the Republic of Cuba, is an island country in the Caribbean. It comprises the main island of Cuba along with thousands of smaller islands, islets, and cays. Situated at the convergence of the Caribbean Sea, the Gulf of Mexico, and the Atlantic Ocean, it lies east of the Yucatán Peninsula, south of Florida and the Bahamas, west of Hispaniola, and north of Jamaica and the Cayman Islands. Havana is the capital and largest city. Cuba is among the most populous countries in the Caribbean.",
  "curaçao": "Curaçao, officially the Country of Curaçao, is a constituent country within the Kingdom of the Netherlands. It is an island country in the southern Caribbean Sea, in the Dutch Caribbean region, lying north of Venezuela and southeast of Aruba. Curaçao includes the main island of the same name and the much smaller, uninhabited island of Klein Curaçao. Its capital is Willemstad. Its name Klein Curaçao translates as \"Little Curaçao\".",
  "cyprus": "Cyprus, officially the Republic of Cyprus, is an island country in the eastern Mediterranean Sea, off the coast of the Levant mainland in West Asia. It is among the largest and most populous islands in the Mediterranean, and it is divided along the United Nations Buffer Zone between the internationally recognised Republic of Cyprus and the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus, which is recognised only by Turkey. The south of the island also hosts the British sovereign military bases of Akrotiri and Dhekelia. The capital and largest city is Nicosia. Cyprus was first settled by hunter-gatherers around 13,000 years ago, with farming communities emerging by the 9th millennium BC.",
  "czechia": "The Czech Republic, also known as Czechia and historically as Bohemia, is a landlocked country in Central Europe. It is bordered by Austria to the south, Germany to the west, Poland to the northeast, and Slovakia to the southeast. The country has a hilly landscape and a mostly temperate continental and oceanic climate. Its capital and largest city is Prague, while other major cities and urban areas include Brno, Ostrava, Plzeň, and Liberec. The Duchy of Bohemia was founded in the late 9th century under Great Moravia.",
  "côte d'ivoire": "Ivory Coast, also known as Côte d'Ivoire and officially the Republic of Côte d'Ivoire, is a country on the southern coast of West Africa. Its political capital, Yamoussoukro, lies in the centre of the country, while Abidjan is its largest city and economic centre. It borders Guinea and Mali to the northwest, Liberia to the west, Burkina Faso to the northeast, Ghana to the east, and the Atlantic Ocean's Gulf of Guinea to the south. It is one of the most populous countries in West Africa. Its official language is French, and indigenous languages are also widely used, including Bété, Baoulé, Dyula, Dan, Anyin, and Cebaara Senufo.",
  "dahomey": "The Kingdom of Dahomey was a West African kingdom located within the present-day Republic of Benin that existed from approximately 1600 until 1904. It developed on the Abomey Plateau among the Fon people in the early 17th century and became a regional power in the 18th century. It expanded south to conquer key coastal cities such as Whydah, gaining unhindered access to the Atlantic slave trade. Ending its tributary status to the Oyo Empire, Dahomey became a key regional state for much of the middle 19th century. European visitors extensively documented the kingdom, making it one of the most familiar African states known to Europeans.",
  "dem. rep. congo": "The Democratic Republic of the Congo, also known as DR Congo, Congo-Kinshasa, or simply the Congo, and formerly named Zaire, is a country in Central Africa. By land area, it is the second-largest country in Africa and among the largest in the world. It is one of the most populous countries in Africa and the most populous Francophone country in the world. French is the official and most widely spoken language. There are over 200 indigenous languages, of which Lingala is among the most widely spoken.",
  "denmark": "Denmark is a Nordic country in Northern Europe. It is the metropole and most populous constituent of the Kingdom of Denmark, a unitary state that also includes the autonomous territories of the Faroe Islands and Greenland in the North Atlantic. Metropolitan Denmark consists of the northern Jutland peninsula and an archipelago of hundreds of islands. It is the southernmost of the Scandinavian countries, lying southwest of Sweden, south of Norway, and north of Germany, with which it shares a short border. Denmark proper is situated between the North Sea to the west and the Baltic Sea to the east.",
  "dhekelia": "Dhekelia, formally Dhekelia Cantonment, is a British military base on the island of Cyprus, administered as part of the Sovereign Base Areas of Akrotiri and Dhekelia, a British Overseas Territory. It is the larger of the two British military bases on the island and is home to Alexander Barracks. It forms part of British Forces Cyprus. The cantonment contains the village of Dasaki Achnas and a portion of the village of Pergamos. It also encloses several Cypriot enclaves, including Xylotymbo, Ormidhia, and the Dhekelia Power Station.",
  "djibouti": "Djibouti, officially the Republic of Djibouti, is a country in the Horn of Africa. It is bordered by Somalia to the south, Ethiopia to the southwest, Eritrea to the north, and the Red Sea and the Gulf of Aden to the east. In antiquity, the territory, together with neighbouring lands, was part of the Land of Punt, while nearby Zeila was later the seat of the medieval Adal and Ifat Sultanates. In the late 19th century, the colony of French Somaliland was established after local Somali and Afar sultans signed treaties with the French. Its railroad to Dire Dawa and later Addis Ababa allowed it to quickly supersede Zeila as the port for southern Ethiopia and the Ogaden.",
  "dominica": "Dominica, officially the Commonwealth of Dominica, is an island country in the Caribbean. It is part of the Windward Islands chain in the Lesser Antilles archipelago in the Caribbean Sea. The capital, Roseau, is located on the western side of the island. Its closest neighbours are two overseas departments of France: Guadeloupe to the northwest and Martinique to the south-southeast. The island is notably mountainous, with its highest point at Morne Diablotins.",
  "dominican rep.": "The Dominican Republic is a country occupying the eastern portion of the Caribbean island of Hispaniola in the Greater Antilles. It shares a maritime border with Puerto Rico to the east and a land border with Haiti to the west, taking up the eastern five-eighths of Hispaniola. Along with Saint Martin, Hispaniola is one of only two islands in the Caribbean shared by two sovereign states. It is one of the larger and more populous nations of the Antilles, second in area only to Cuba. Its capital and principal metropolitan center is Santo Domingo.",
  "dominican republic": "The Dominican Republic is a country occupying the eastern portion of the Caribbean island of Hispaniola in the Greater Antilles. It shares a maritime border with Puerto Rico to the east and a land border with Haiti to the west, taking up the eastern five-eighths of Hispaniola. Along with Saint Martin, Hispaniola is one of only two islands in the Caribbean shared by two sovereign states. It is one of the larger and more populous nations of the Antilles, second in area only to Cuba. Its capital and principal metropolitan center is Santo Domingo.",
  "dutch guiana": "Dutch Guiana, more formally the colony of Surinam, was a Dutch plantation colony on the northeastern coast of South America and the predecessor of the modern country of Suriname. It came under Dutch control in 1667, when the Netherlands took the settlement from England during the Second Anglo-Dutch War and retained it in the settlement that also transferred New Amsterdam to the English. Its colonial economy was built on plantations producing crops such as sugar, coffee, cotton, and cacao, worked for nearly two centuries by enslaved Africans until slavery was abolished in 1863. After emancipation the colony recruited large numbers of indentured labourers from British India and the Dutch East Indies, giving the territory a markedly diverse population. Dutch Guiana remained a colony of the Netherlands until 1954, when it became a constituent country of the Kingdom of the Netherlands, and it achieved full independence as Suriname in 1975.",
  "ecuador": "Ecuador, officially the Republic of Ecuador, is a country in northwestern South America, bordered by Colombia to the north, Peru to the east and south, and the Pacific Ocean to the west. Its territory also includes the Galápagos Islands, lying in the Pacific well to the west of the mainland. The capital is Quito, while the largest city is Guayaquil. The land was home to several indigenous peoples who were gradually incorporated into the Inca Empire during the 15th century before Spanish colonization in the 16th century. It achieved independence in 1820 as part of Gran Colombia, emerging as a sovereign state in 1830.",
  "egypt": "Egypt, officially the Arab Republic of Egypt, is a country spanning the northeast corner of Africa and, via the Sinai Peninsula, the southwest corner of Asia. It is bordered by the Mediterranean Sea to the north, Palestine and Israel to the northeast, the Red Sea to the east, Sudan and the Sahara to the south, and Libya to the west, with the Gulf of Aqaba separating it from Jordan and Saudi Arabia. Cairo is the capital, largest city, and leading cultural center, while Alexandria is the second-largest city and an important hub of industry and tourism. It is one of the most populous countries of both the Arab world and the African continent. It also ranks among the most populous countries in the world as a whole.",
  "el salvador": "El Salvador, officially the Republic of El Salvador, is a country in Central America. It is bordered to the northeast by Honduras, to the northwest by Guatemala, and to the south by the Pacific Ocean. Its capital and largest city is San Salvador. Among the Mesoamerican nations that historically controlled the region were the Maya. The Cuzcatlecs were also among the peoples who held sway over the area.",
  "eq. guinea": "Equatorial Guinea, officially the Republic of Equatorial Guinea, is a country on the west coast of Central Africa and the only Spanish-speaking country in Africa. Formerly the colony of Spanish Guinea, its post-independence name refers to its location both near the Equator and within the African region of Guinea. Its territory includes a mainland section as well as islands, among them Bioko in the Gulf of Guinea. Most of its people belong to the Fang, the country's dominant ethnic group. The Bubi people, indigenous to Bioko, form the second-largest group.",
  "eritrea": "Eritrea, officially the State of Eritrea, is a country in the Horn of Africa region of East Africa. Its capital and largest city is Asmara. It is bordered by Ethiopia to the south, Sudan to the west, and Djibouti to the southeast. The northeastern and eastern parts of the country have an extensive coastline along the Red Sea. Its territory also includes the Dahlak Archipelago and several of the Hanish Islands.",
  "estonia": "Estonia, officially the Republic of Estonia, is a country in the Baltic region of Northern Europe. It is bordered to the north by the Gulf of Finland across from Finland, to the west by the Baltic Sea across from Sweden, to the south by Latvia, and to the east by Russia. Its territory consists of the mainland together with the larger islands of Saaremaa and Hiiumaa and more than two thousand smaller islands and islets on the eastern coast of the Baltic Sea. The capital, Tallinn, along with the city of Tartu, are the country's two largest urban areas. The Estonian language, of the Finnic family, is the official language and the first language of most of its people.",
  "eswatini": "Eswatini, formally the Kingdom of Eswatini and historically called KaNgwane, is a landlocked country in Southern Africa also known by its former name Swaziland. It is bordered by South Africa on all sides except the east, where it shares a border with Mozambique. It is one of the smallest countries in Africa, measuring no more than a couple hundred kilometers in either direction. Despite its size, its climate and topography are diverse, ranging from a cool and mountainous highveld to a hot and dry lowveld. The executive capital and largest city is Mbabane, while Lobamba serves as the legislative and second capital.",
  "ethiopia": "Ethiopia, officially the Federal Democratic Republic of Ethiopia, is a landlocked country in the Horn of Africa region of East Africa. It shares borders with Eritrea to the north, Djibouti to the northeast, Somalia to the east, Kenya to the south, and South Sudan to the west. Sudan lies to its northwest. It is one of the most populous countries in the world and among the most populous in Africa. The national capital and largest city, Addis Ababa, lies just west of the East African Rift, which splits the country between the African and Somali tectonic plates.",
  "faeroe is.": "The Faroe Islands, also known as the Faroes, are an archipelago in the North Atlantic Ocean and an autonomous territory of the Kingdom of Denmark. They lie between Iceland, Norway, and the Hebrides and Shetland isles of Scotland. The official language is Faroese, which is partially mutually intelligible with Icelandic. The terrain is rugged, dominated by fjords and cliffs with sparse vegetation and few trees. Owing to their proximity to the Arctic Circle they experience long summer twilight and short winter days, yet a subpolar oceanic climate and the Gulf Stream keep temperatures mild year-round.",
  "falkland is.": "The Falkland Islands, known in Spanish as the Islas Malvinas and commonly called the Falklands, are an archipelago in the South Atlantic Ocean on the Patagonian Shelf. The principal islands lie a few hundred kilometers east of South America's southern Patagonian coast, at a latitude of about 52 degrees south. The archipelago comprises East Falkland, West Falkland, and hundreds of smaller islands. As a British Overseas Territory, the Falklands have internal self-governance while the United Kingdom takes responsibility for their defence and foreign affairs. The capital and largest settlement is Stanley, on East Falkland.",
  "fiji": "Fiji, officially the Republic of Fiji, is an archipelagic country in Melanesia, part of Oceania in the South Pacific Ocean. It lies to the north-northeast of New Zealand across a broad stretch of open ocean. Fiji consists of an archipelago of more than three hundred islands, of which about a hundred are permanently inhabited, together with more than five hundred islets. The most outlying island group is Ono-i-Lau. The great majority of the population lives on the two major islands, Viti Levu and Vanua Levu.",
  "finland": "Finland, officially the Republic of Finland, is a Nordic country in Northern Europe. It borders Sweden to the northwest, Norway to the north, and Russia to the east, with the Gulf of Bothnia to the west and the Gulf of Finland to the south, opposite Estonia. Its capital and largest city is Helsinki. Finnish and Swedish are its official languages, with Finnish spoken by the great majority of the population. Swedish is the mother tongue of a smaller share of its inhabitants.",
  "fr. polynesia": "French Polynesia is an overseas collectivity of France and its sole overseas country, located in the South Pacific Ocean. It comprises well over a hundred geographically dispersed islands and atolls stretching across more than two thousand kilometres of ocean. The territory is associated with the European Union as an overseas country and territory. The largest share of its population lives in the Society Islands, with the remainder spread across the rest of the archipelago. It is classified by the United Nations as a non-self-governing territory.",
  "fr. s. antarctic lands": "The French Southern and Antarctic Lands, abbreviated TAAF, form an overseas territory of France scattered across the far southern reaches of the globe. The territory includes Adélie Land, the French claim on the continent of Antarctica. It also encompasses the Crozet Islands and the Kerguelen Islands, groups of volcanic islands in the southern Indian Ocean south of Madagascar and southeast of Africa. Saint Paul and Amsterdam Islands, lying to the north of the Kerguelen group, are likewise part of the territory. Together these scattered island groups and the Antarctic claim make up the whole of the territory.",
  "france": "France, officially the French Republic, is a country primarily located in Western Europe, alongside overseas regions and territories on several continents. Its overseas holdings include French Guiana in South America, Saint Pierre and Miquelon in the North Atlantic, the French West Indies, and numerous islands in Oceania and the Indian Ocean. Metropolitan France shares borders with Belgium and Luxembourg to the north, Germany to the northeast, Switzerland to the east, Italy and Monaco to the southeast, and Andorra and Spain to the south, with a maritime border with the United Kingdom to the northwest. Its metropolitan territory extends from the Rhine to the Atlantic Ocean and from the Mediterranean Sea to the English Channel and the North Sea. Its overseas presence spans South America, the North Atlantic, the West Indies, Oceania, and the Indian Ocean.",
  "french guiana": "French Guiana, also known by its French name Guyane, is an overseas department and region of France on the northern coast of South America. It is bordered by Suriname to the west and Brazil to the east and south, and lies within the Guianas and the West Indies. It is the second-largest region of France and the largest outermost region within the European Union, roughly one-seventh the size of European France. It has a very low population density. Its territory covers a large land area on the northern South American coast.",
  "french indochina": "French Indochina, officially the Indochinese Union and later the Indochinese Federation, was a grouping of French dependent territories in Southeast Asia established in 1887 and dissolved in 1954. It began as a federation of French colonies and later became a confederation of French associated states. Its constituent parts included Cambodia, Laos, the leased territory of Guangzhouwan, Cochinchina, and the Vietnamese regions of Tonkin and Annam. It served as the framework for French colonial rule across the region for several decades. In 1949, Vietnam was reunited and regained Cochinchina.",
  "futa jalon": "Fouta Djallon is a highland region in West Africa, located in the center of Guinea. It roughly corresponds with the area known as Middle Guinea. The region lies in the interior of Guinea, in West Africa. Its name is also rendered in Fula and Arabic forms. It is one of the recognized geographic regions of Guinea.",
  "futa toro": "Futa Toro, often called simply the Futa, is a semidesert region along the middle run of the Senegal River, located in present-day Senegal. It is historically significant as the center of several Fulani states and as a source of jihad armies and of migrants to Fouta Djallon. The name combines Futa, a general term the Fulbe applied to the areas they inhabited, with Toro, the region's own identity, likely derived from the ancient kingdom of Takrur. Most of its people speak Pulaar, a dialect of the Fula language spoken across West Africa from Senegal to Cameroon. They identify themselves through this language as the Haalpulaar'en, meaning those who speak Pulaar.",
  "gabon": "Gabon, officially the Gabonese Republic, is a country on the Atlantic coast of Central Africa, lying on the equator. It is bordered by Equatorial Guinea to the northwest, Cameroon to the north, the Republic of the Congo to the east and south, and the Gulf of Guinea to the west. Its landscape includes coastal plains, interior mountains such as the Cristal Mountains and the Chaillu Massif, and savanna in the east. Libreville is the country's capital and largest city. Its original inhabitants were the Bambenga.",
  "gambia": "The Gambia, officially the Republic of The Gambia, is a country in West Africa and the smallest country in continental Africa. It is bounded by Senegal on all sides except for its western coast, which faces the Atlantic Ocean. Its territory follows both banks of the lower Gambia River, which flows through the center of the country and empties into the Atlantic, giving the nation its distinctive elongated shape. Its capital is the island city of Banjul, formerly called Bathurst during the colonial era. Banjul is the most extensive metropolitan area in the country.",
  "georgia": "Georgia most commonly refers to a country in the South Caucasus region. The name may also refer to a state in the southeastern United States. As a place name it is shared by these two otherwise distinct entities. The South Caucasus country is one of its principal meanings. The United States state is the other most common meaning of the name.",
  "germany": "Germany, officially the Federal Republic of Germany, is a country in Western and Central Europe. It lies between the Baltic Sea and the North Sea to the north and reaches the Alps to the south. It borders Denmark to the north; Poland and the Czech Republic to the east; Austria and Switzerland to the south; and France, Luxembourg, Belgium, and the Netherlands to the west. It is organized as a federation of sixteen constituent states and is among the most populous countries in Europe. Its capital and largest city is Berlin, while Frankfurt is a major financial centre and the Ruhr is its largest urban area.",
  "ghana": "Ghana, officially the Republic of Ghana, is a country in West Africa. It lies along the Gulf of Guinea and the Atlantic Ocean to the south and shares borders with Ivory Coast to the west, Burkina Faso to the north, and Togo to the east. Its territory spans varied ecologies, ranging from coastal savannas to tropical rainforests. It is among the more populous countries of West Africa and the wider continent. Its capital and most populous city is Accra.",
  "gibraltar": "Gibraltar is a British Overseas Territory and city at the southern tip of the Iberian Peninsula, on the Bay of Gibraltar near where the Mediterranean Sea meets the Atlantic Ocean through the Strait of Gibraltar. It is bordered to the north by Spain, in the area known as the Campo de Gibraltar. Its landscape is dominated by the Rock of Gibraltar, at the foot of which lies a densely populated town area. Its inhabitants are primarily Gibraltarians. It was founded as a permanent watchtower by the Almohads in 1160.",
  "greece": "Greece, officially the Hellenic Republic, occupies the southern tip of the Balkan peninsula in Southeast Europe. Made up of a mainland and thousands of islands, it has the longest coastline on the Mediterranean, with the Ionian Sea to the west and the Aegean Sea to the east. It is bordered by Albania to the northwest and by North Macedonia and Bulgaria to the north, while Turkey lies to the east across both land and the Aegean. The capital, Athens, is the largest city, followed by Thessaloniki and Patras. The country is organized into nine regions, and its thousands of islands make up much of its territory.",
  "greenland": "Greenland is an autonomous territory of the Kingdom of Denmark. It is the largest of the kingdom's three constituent parts by land area, the others being Denmark proper and the Faroe Islands. Its people are citizens of Denmark and thus of the European Union, although Greenland itself is not part of the EU. It is the world's largest island, lying between the Arctic and Atlantic oceans, east of the Canadian Arctic Archipelago. It shares a short border with Canada on Hans Island in the far north.",
  "grenada": "Grenada is an archipelagic country of the West Indies in the eastern Caribbean Sea. It is the southernmost of the Windward Islands, lying directly south of Saint Vincent and the Grenadines. It also sits to the north of Trinidad and the South American mainland. The country consists of the main island of Grenada together with the smaller islands of Carriacou and Petite Martinique, plus several islets to the north that form part of the Grenadines. Its capital is St George's, situated on the main island.",
  "griqualand west": "Griqualand West is a region of central South Africa that now forms part of the Northern Cape Province. It was inhabited by the Griqua, a semi-nomadic, Afrikaans-speaking people of mixed-race origin who established several states beyond the expanding frontier of the Cape Colony. The area was also an ancestral home to the Tswana and Khoisan peoples. In 1873 it was proclaimed a British colony, with its capital at Kimberley, and in 1880 it was annexed by the Cape Colony. When the Union of South Africa was formed in 1910, Griqualand West became part of the Cape Province while retaining its own regional sports teams.",
  "guadeloupe": "Guadeloupe is an overseas department and region of the French Republic located in the Caribbean. It is made up of several inhabited islands, chiefly Basse-Terre, Grande-Terre, Marie-Galante, La Désirade, and the Îles des Saintes, along with numerous smaller islets. It lies south of Antigua and Barbuda and Montserrat and north of Dominica. The capital, Basse-Terre, sits on the southwestern coast of Basse-Terre Island, while the main centre of business is Pointe-à-Pitre on Grande-Terre Island. The most populous city is Les Abymes, also on Grande-Terre Island.",
  "guam": "Guam is an island that is an organized, unincorporated territory of the United States in the Micronesia subregion of the western Pacific Ocean. Its capital is Hagåtña, while its most populous village is Dededo. It is the westernmost point and territory of the United States as measured from the country's geographic center. In Oceania, Guam is the largest and southernmost of the Mariana Islands and the largest island in Micronesia. The geographic center from which it is measured is marked by point Udall.",
  "guatemala": "Guatemala, officially the Republic of Guatemala, is a country in northern Central America. It is bordered by Mexico to the north and west, Belize to the northeast, Honduras to the east, and El Salvador to the southeast, with the Pacific Ocean to the south and the Gulf of Honduras to the northeast. The territory of modern Guatemala hosted the core of the Maya civilization, which extended across Mesoamerica. In the 16th century most of this land was conquered by the Spanish and claimed as part of the viceroyalty of New Spain. Guatemala attained independence from Spain and Mexico in 1821.",
  "guernsey": "Guernsey is the second-largest of the Channel Islands, lying to the west of the Cotentin Peninsula in Normandy. It is the largest island in the Bailiwick of Guernsey, which also includes the inhabited islands of Alderney, Herm, Jethou, Lihou, and Sark, along with many smaller islets and rocks. Guernsey formed part of the Duchy of Normandy until 1204, when the Channel Islands remained loyal to the English crown after splitting from mainland Normandy. In 1290 the Channel Islands were divided administratively, and Guernsey became part of the Bailiwick of Guernsey. Most of the bailiwick's population lives on the island of Guernsey itself.",
  "guinea": "Guinea, officially the Republic of Guinea, is a coastal country in West Africa. It borders the Atlantic Ocean to the west, Guinea-Bissau to the northwest, Senegal to the north, Mali to the northeast, Ivory Coast to the southeast, and Sierra Leone and Liberia to the south. It is sometimes called Guinea-Conakry, after its capital Conakry, to distinguish it from other territories in the region such as Guinea-Bissau and Equatorial Guinea. Formerly known as French Guinea, it achieved independence in 1958. The name distinguishes it from the wider eponymous region that shares the name Guinea.",
  "guinea-bissau": "Guinea-Bissau, officially the Republic of Guinea-Bissau, is a country in West Africa. It borders Senegal to the north and Guinea to the southeast. The region was once part of the kingdom of Kaabu and of the Mali Empire, and parts of Kaabu persisted into the 18th century. From the 16th century some areas came under the influence of the Portuguese Empire, and in the 19th century the territory was colonised as Portuguese Guinea. It takes its modern name from the former colony of Portuguese Guinea.",
  "guyana": "Guyana, officially the Co-operative Republic of Guyana, is a country on the northern coast of South America. It is bordered by the Atlantic Ocean to the north, Suriname to the east, Brazil to the south and southwest, and Venezuela to the west. It forms part of the region known as The Guianas. The capital and largest city is Georgetown, on the Atlantic coast. It is among the smallest and least densely populated of the sovereign states of mainland South America.",
  "haiti": "Haiti, officially the Republic of Haiti, is a country in the Caribbean on the island of Hispaniola, east of Cuba and Jamaica and south of The Bahamas. It occupies the western side of the island, which it shares with the Dominican Republic. Haiti is among the larger countries of the Caribbean by area and one of its most populous. The capital and largest city is Port-au-Prince. The island was originally inhabited by the Indigenous Taíno people before European colonization.",
  "heard i. and mcdonald is.": "The Territory of Heard Island and McDonald Islands is an Australian external territory in the southern Indian Ocean. Discovered in the mid-19th century, it is a group of sub-Antarctic volcanic islands lying on the Kerguelen Plateau. It sits far to the southwest of the Australian mainland and north of Antarctica. The territory contains Australia's only active volcanoes and its highest point outside the Australian Antarctic Territory, Mawson Peak. Uninhabited and difficult to reach, it has been described as one of the most remote places on Earth.",
  "honduras": "Honduras, officially the Republic of Honduras, is a country in Central America. It is bordered by Guatemala to the west, El Salvador to the southwest, and Nicaragua to the southeast, with the Pacific Ocean to the south at the Gulf of Fonseca and the Caribbean Sea to the north at the Gulf of Honduras. Its capital and largest city is Tegucigalpa. Before Spanish colonization in the sixteenth century, Honduras was home to several important Mesoamerican cultures, most notably the Maya. The Spanish introduced Catholicism and the now-predominant Spanish language, along with customs that blended with indigenous culture.",
  "hong kong": "Hong Kong is a special administrative region of China, situated on the country's southern coast just south of Shenzhen. It consists of Hong Kong Island, the Kowloon Peninsula, and the New Territories, and ranks among the most densely populated territories in the world. It was established as a colony of the British Empire after the Qing dynasty ceded Hong Kong Island following its defeat in the First Opium War. The colony expanded to Kowloon in 1860 and was further extended when the United Kingdom obtained a 99-year lease of the New Territories in 1898. This colonial legacy shaped its distinct status, blending Chinese and British influences within a single densely built maritime hub.",
  "hungary": "Hungary is a landlocked country in Central Europe, spanning much of the Carpathian Basin. It is bordered by Slovakia to the north, Ukraine to the northeast, Romania to the east and southeast, Serbia to the south, Croatia and Slovenia to the southwest, and Austria to the west. The land lies within the Danube River's drainage basin and is dominated by great lowland plains. Its population consists mostly of ethnic Hungarians, or Magyars, alongside a significant Romani minority. Hungarian is the official language and is among the few in Europe that lie outside the Indo-European family.",
  "ibadan": "Ibadan is the capital and most populous city of Oyo State in Nigeria, and bears a Yoruba name. It ranks among the largest cities in Nigeria and is the country's largest city by land area. At the time of Nigeria's independence in 1960, it was the largest and most populous city in the country, and among the most populous in Africa. It has since been ranked one of the fastest-growing cities in sub-Saharan Africa. It remains a major urban center of the country.",
  "iceland": "Iceland is a Nordic island country between the Arctic Ocean and the North Atlantic Ocean, lying on the Mid-Atlantic Ridge between Europe and North America. It is culturally and politically linked with Europe and is the region's westernmost and most sparsely populated country. Its capital and largest city is Reykjavík, home to a large share of the country's residents. The official language is Icelandic. Situated on a rift between tectonic plates, the island is highly geologically active, with geysers and frequent volcanic eruptions.",
  "imerina": "The Kingdom of Imerina, also known as the Kingdom of Merina or the Kingdom of Madagascar, was a pre-colonial state off the coast of Southeast Africa that came to dominate most of what is now Madagascar. It spread outward from Imerina, the Central Highlands region primarily inhabited by the Merina ethnic group, with a spiritual capital at Ambohimanga and a political capital to the west at Antananarivo, still the seat of government today. Its rulers descended from a long line of hereditary Merina royalty tracing back to Andriamanelo, traditionally credited with founding Imerina. By the 18th century the kingdom had extended its authority across much of the island. Its monarchs reigned over greater Madagascar through the 19th century until the state's dissolution.",
  "imperial japan": "The Empire of Japan, also known as Imperial Japan, was the period of Japanese history that began with the Meiji Restoration in 1868 and ended with the ratification of the postwar Constitution of Japan in 1947. At its height it encompassed the Japanese archipelago along with the Kuril Islands, Karafuto, Korea, and Taiwan. Dependent territories such as the South Seas Mandate and leased concessions like the Kwantung Leased Territory were governed as outlying possessions rather than internal parts of the empire. The era was marked by territorial expansion across East Asia and the Pacific. It came to a close with the establishment of a new constitutional order.",
  "india": "India, officially the Republic of India, is a country in South Asia and one of the largest nations in the world by area. Bounded by the Indian Ocean to the south, the Arabian Sea to the southwest, and the Bay of Bengal to the southeast, it shares land borders with Pakistan to the west; China, Nepal, and Bhutan to the north; and Bangladesh and Myanmar to the east. In the Indian Ocean it lies near Sri Lanka and the Maldives, while its Andaman and Nicobar Islands share maritime borders with Myanmar, Thailand, and Indonesia. Since gaining independence in 1947, it has been the world's most populous democracy. It is also the most populous country in the world.",
  "indonesia": "Indonesia, officially the Republic of Indonesia, is a country in Southeast Asia and Oceania, spanning the seas between the Indian and Pacific oceans. Comprising over 17,000 islands, including Sumatra, Java, Sulawesi, and parts of Borneo and New Guinea, it is the world's largest archipelagic state. It contains significant areas of wilderness that support one of the world's highest levels of biodiversity. It shares land borders with Papua New Guinea, Timor-Leste, and Malaysia, as well as maritime borders with several other countries, including Australia, Singapore, and the Philippines. This sprawling island geography underpins its rich ecological diversity.",
  "iran": "Iran, officially the Islamic Republic of Iran and historically known as Persia, is a country in West Asia. It borders Iraq to the west; Turkey, Azerbaijan, and Armenia to the northwest; the Caspian Sea to the north; Turkmenistan to the northeast; Afghanistan to the east; Pakistan to the southeast; and the Gulf of Oman and the Persian Gulf to the south. The country is divided into five regions comprising thirty-one provinces. Tehran is the nation's capital and largest city and serves as its primary economic center. It ranks among the larger countries in the world in both geographic size and population.",
  "iraq": "Iraq, officially the Republic of Iraq, is a country in West Asia within the Middle East. It is bordered by Saudi Arabia to the south, Turkey to the north, Iran to the east, the Persian Gulf and Kuwait to the southeast, Jordan to the southwest, and Syria to the west. Baghdad is the capital and largest city in the country. Beginning in the 6th millennium BC, the fertile plains between the Tigris and Euphrates rivers, known as Mesopotamia, fostered the rise of early cities, civilizations, and empires. These included Sumer, Akkad, Babylonia, and Assyria.",
  "ireland": "Ireland is an island in the North Atlantic Ocean, in Northwestern Europe. Geopolitically it is divided between the Republic of Ireland, a sovereign state covering five-sixths of the island, and Northern Ireland, which is part of the United Kingdom and covers the remaining sixth. It is separated from Great Britain to its east by the North Channel, the Irish Sea, and St George's Channel. Ireland is the second-largest island of the British Isles, the third-largest in Europe, and among the largest in the world. Its history and identity are shaped by this partition and its close, complex relationship with neighboring Britain.",
  "isle of man": "The Isle of Man, known in Manx as Mannin, is a self-governing British Crown Dependency in the Irish Sea, lying between Great Britain and Ireland. As head of state, the British monarch holds the title Lord of Mann and is represented on the island by a Lieutenant Governor. The government of the United Kingdom is responsible for the island's military defence and represents it abroad, though the Isle of Man retains a separate international identity. Humans have lived on the island since prehistoric times, well before 6500 BC. Gaelic cultural influence and settlement arrived by the 5th century AD, and the Manx language emerged as a branch of the Goidelic languages.",
  "israel": "Israel, officially the State of Israel, is a country in the Southern Levant region of West Asia. It is bordered by Lebanon to the north, Syria to the northeast, Jordan to the east, and Egypt to the southwest. Its western coast lies on the Mediterranean Sea, its southern tip reaches the Red Sea, and to the east lies Earth's lowest point near the Dead Sea. Jerusalem is the government seat and proclaimed capital, while Tel Aviv is the largest urban area and economic center. The Land of Israel, also called Palestine or the Holy Land, was home to the ancient Canaanites and later the kingdoms of Israel and Judah and Hasmonean Judea.",
  "italy": "Italy, officially the Italian Republic, is a country in Southern and Western Europe. It consists of a peninsula that extends into the Mediterranean Sea, with the Alps along its northern land border, as well as numerous islands, notably Sicily and Sardinia. It shares land borders with France to the west; Switzerland and Austria to the north; Slovenia to the east; and the two enclaves of Vatican City and San Marino. Its capital and largest city is Rome, while other major cities include Milan, Naples, Turin, Palermo, Bologna, Florence, Genoa, Bari, and Venice. It is one of the larger countries in Europe by area and among the most populous member states of the European Union.",
  "ivory coast": "Ivory Coast, also known as Côte d'Ivoire and officially the Republic of Côte d'Ivoire, is a country on the southern coast of West Africa. Its political capital, Yamoussoukro, lies in the centre of the country, while Abidjan is its largest city and economic centre. It borders Guinea and Mali to the northwest, Liberia to the west, Burkina Faso to the northeast, and Ghana to the east, with the Atlantic Ocean's Gulf of Guinea forming its southern coast. It is one of the most populous countries in West Africa. French is its official language, while numerous indigenous languages, including Bété, Baoulé, Dyula, Dan, Anyin, and Cebaara Senufo, remain widely used.",
  "jamaica": "Jamaica is an island country in the Caribbean and the third-largest island in the Greater Antilles, after Cuba and the island of Hispaniola. It lies south of Cuba, west of Hispaniola, and southeast of the Cayman Islands. Kingston is the country's capital and largest city. Jamaica is one of the more populous Anglophone countries in the Americas and a leading population centre within the Caribbean. Hispaniola, its neighbour to the west, contains both Haiti and the Dominican Republic.",
  "japan": "Japan is an island country in East Asia, located in the Pacific Ocean off the northeast coast of the Asian mainland. It is bordered to the west by the Sea of Japan and extends from the Sea of Okhotsk in the north to the East China Sea in the south. The Japanese archipelago consists of four major islands alongside thousands of smaller ones, and the country is divided into 47 administrative prefectures and eight traditional regions. Most of its terrain is mountainous and heavily forested, concentrating agriculture and its highly urbanized population along the eastern coastal plains. It is one of the world's most populous countries.",
  "jersey": "Jersey, officially the Bailiwick of Jersey, is an autonomous and self-governing British Crown Dependency in northwestern Europe, lying off the Cotentin Peninsula of north-west France. The main island, Jersey, is the largest of the Channel Islands, and the bailiwick also includes several surrounding uninhabited islands and rocks. Although not a sovereign state, it has its own legal, fiscal, and governmental systems, on which basis it is regarded as a small nation or island country. Jèrriais, a Norman language, is part of its traditional cultural heritage. It is a Crown Dependency and thus lies outside the United Kingdom while being closely associated with the British Crown.",
  "jordan": "Jordan, officially the Hashemite Kingdom of Jordan, is a country in the Southern Levant region of West Asia. It is bordered by Syria to the north, Iraq to the east, Saudi Arabia to the south, and both Israel and Palestine's West Bank to the west. The Jordan River, flowing into the Dead Sea, runs along its western border within the Jordan Rift Valley. In the southwest a small coastline along the Red Sea is separated by the Gulf of Aqaba from Egypt. Amman is the country's capital and largest city, as well as the most populous city in the Levant.",
  "kanem-bornu": "The Kanem–Bornu Empire was an empire based around Lake Chad that once ruled areas now part of Nigeria, Niger, Cameroon, Libya, Algeria, Sudan, and Chad. Sustained by the prosperous trans-Saharan trade, it was one of the oldest and longest-lived empires in world history and especially in African history. Its early history is poorly known, but it is believed to have been founded around the year 700, though later and earlier dates have been proposed. The Duguwa dynasty ruled from the capital Njimi in the Kanem region, in modern-day Chad. Its rulers used the title mai.",
  "kazakhstan": "Kazakhstan, officially the Republic of Kazakhstan, is a landlocked country situated primarily in Central Asia, with a portion of its territory extending into Eastern Europe. It borders Russia to the north and west, China to the east, Kyrgyzstan to the southeast, Uzbekistan to the south, and Turkmenistan to the southwest, and it has a coastline along the Caspian Sea. The capital is Astana, while the largest city and principal cultural and economic centre is Almaty, which served as the capital until 1997. It is the world's largest landlocked country and one of the largest countries overall by land area. Hilly plateaus and plains account for much of its vast territory, with lowlands forming another portion and mountainous regions along its southern and eastern frontiers.",
  "kenya": "Kenya, officially the Republic of Kenya, is a country located in East Africa. It is among the most populous countries on the African continent. Its capital and largest city is Nairobi, while the second-largest and oldest city is the port of Mombasa, located on Mombasa Island. Other major cities include Kisumu, Nakuru, and Eldoret. It ranks among the most populous nations in Africa and the wider world.",
  "kingdom of brazil": "The Kingdom of Brazil, in Portuguese Reino do Brasil, was a constituent kingdom of the United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves. As a constituent kingdom, it formed one of the component parts of that larger united kingdom. Its name in Portuguese was rendered Reino do Brasil. It was thus not an independent state but a member kingdom within the United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves. In this way Brazil held the formal standing of a kingdom within that union.",
  "kingdom of hawaii": "The Hawaiian Kingdom, also known as the Kingdom of Hawaiʻi, was an archipelagic country that eventually encompassed all of the inhabited Hawaiian Islands. It was established when Kamehameha I, then Aliʻi nui of Hawaii, conquered Oʻahu, Maui, Molokaʻi, and Lānaʻi and unified them under one government. The islands were fully unified when Kauaʻi and Niʻihau voluntarily joined the kingdom. Two major dynastic families ruled it, the House of Kamehameha and the House of Kalākaua. The kingdom gained diplomatic recognition from European powers and the United States.",
  "kiribati": "Kiribati, officially the Republic of Kiribati, is an archipelagic country spanning the Micronesia and Polynesia sub-regions of Oceania in the central Pacific Ocean. It comprises 32 atolls and other islands together with one remote raised coral island, Banaba. Its small land area is dispersed across an enormous expanse of ocean, giving it one of the largest maritime domains in the world. The spread of its islands, from Banaba in the west to Kiritimati in the east, straddles the equator and the 180th meridian. Because of this reach, the International Date Line bends around Kiribati and swings far to the east.",
  "kong": "The Kong Empire, also called the Wattara or Ouattara Empire, was a Dyula Muslim trading and military state founded in the early eighteenth century by Seku Watara and centered on the city of Kong in what is now northeastern Côte d'Ivoire. Established by Mandé merchants whose commercial network reached back to the Mali Empire, it grew into a largely decentralized power built on merchant houses and the protection of long-distance trade routes. At its height in the eighteenth century it extended across parts of present-day Côte d'Ivoire, Burkina Faso, Mali, and Ghana, becoming a major state south of the Niger River. Kong also flourished as a prominent center of Islamic scholarship and Quranic learning in the region. The empire was shattered in 1897–1898 when the forces of Samori Ture sacked and burned the city of Kong, after which the area fell under French colonial control.",
  "korea": "Korea is a peninsular region in East Asia consisting of the Korean Peninsula, Jeju Island, and smaller islands. Since the end of the Second World War in 1945, it has been politically divided at or near the 38th parallel between North Korea and South Korea. Both states proclaimed independence in 1948, and the two fought the Korean War from 1950 to 1953. The region is bordered by China to the north and Russia to the northeast, across the Amnok and Duman rivers, and is separated from Japan to the southeast by the Korea Strait. Known human habitation of the peninsula dates back tens of thousands of years.",
  "kosovo": "Kosovo, officially the Republic of Kosovo, is a landlocked country in Southeast Europe with partial diplomatic recognition. It is bordered by Albania to the southwest, Montenegro to the west, Serbia to the north and east, and North Macedonia to the southeast. The vast majority of its population are ethnic Albanians. Kosovo has a varied terrain of high plains, rolling hills, and mountains, some rising to considerable altitude. Its climate is mainly continental with some Mediterranean and Alpine influences.",
  "kuba": "The Kuba Kingdom was a Central African state in the south-central Congo basin, in the region bounded by the Sankuru, Lulua, and Kasai rivers in what is now the Democratic Republic of the Congo. Founded in the early seventeenth century under the reformer-king Shyaam a-Mbul a Ngoong, it united a cluster of Bushoong-speaking chiefdoms and neighbouring peoples into a single confederation. Its monarch bore the title nyim and was drawn from the ruling Bushoong clan, governing through an elaborate structure of councils, titled offices, and courts that checked royal authority. The kingdom became especially renowned for its arts, including intricate raffia textiles, geometric masks, decorated boxes, and carved ndop portrait figures of its kings. Relatively sheltered by its inland position, it flourished for more than two centuries before European colonization ended its independence in the late nineteenth century, though the Kuba monarchy survives as a traditional institution.",
  "kuwait": "Kuwait, officially the State of Kuwait, is a small country in West Asia situated at the head of the Persian Gulf on the northeastern edge of the Arabian Peninsula. It borders Iraq to the north and Saudi Arabia to the south, and lies close to mainland Iran across a short stretch of Iraqi coastline. The country has a coastline of roughly 500 kilometres along the Gulf. It is effectively a city-state, with most of its inhabitants concentrated in the urban agglomeration of Kuwait City, the capital and largest city. Its population includes both Kuwaiti citizens and a large body of foreign nationals drawn from many countries.",
  "kyrgyzstan": "Kyrgyzstan, officially the Kyrgyz Republic and formerly known as Kirghizia, is a landlocked country in the eastern part of Central Asia. It lies within the Tian Shan and Pamir mountain ranges and is bordered by Kazakhstan to the north, Uzbekistan to the west, Tajikistan to the south, and China to the east and southeast. Its capital and largest city is Bishkek, which sits on the northern border with Kazakhstan. Ethnic Kyrgyz form the majority of the population, alongside significant Uzbek and Russian minorities. The country's history spans a succession of cultures and empires.",
  "lagos": "Lagos, also called Lagos City and known in Yoruba as Èkó, is a large metropolitan port city in southwestern Nigeria. It ranks as the country's largest city and one of the most populous urban areas on the African continent, and among the fastest-growing megacities in the world. Lagos served as Nigeria's national capital until the government's 1991 decision to relocate the capital to Abuja in the centre of the country. It remains a major African financial centre and plays a leading role in the national economy. The city functions as the economic hub both of Lagos State and of Nigeria as a whole.",
  "laos": "Laos, officially the Lao People's Democratic Republic, is a country in mainland Southeast Asia and the region's only landlocked state. It is bordered by Myanmar and China to the northwest, Vietnam to the east, Cambodia to the southeast, and Thailand to the west and southwest. Its capital and most populous city is Vientiane. The country holds three UNESCO World Heritage Sites: the town of Luang Prabang, the temple complex of Vat Phou, and the Plain of Jars. The Boten–Vientiane railway, the Laotian section of the Laos–China Railway, connects Vientiane to Kunming.",
  "latvia": "Latvia, officially the Republic of Latvia, is a country in the Baltic region of northern Europe. It is one of the three Baltic states, together with Estonia to the north and Lithuania to the south. Latvia borders Russia to the east and Belarus to the southeast. It also shares a maritime border with Sweden to the west. The country has a temperate seasonal climate.",
  "lebanon": "Lebanon, officially the Lebanese Republic, is a country in the Levant region of West Asia. Set at the crossroads of the Mediterranean Basin and the Arabian Peninsula, it is bordered by Syria to the north and east, Israel to the south, and the Mediterranean Sea to the west, with Cyprus lying a short distance off its coast. Beirut is the country's capital and largest city. Human habitation in Lebanon dates back to around 5000 BC. Its position on the eastern Mediterranean has long placed it at a meeting point of the Mediterranean world and the Arabian Peninsula.",
  "lesotho": "Lesotho, officially the Kingdom of Lesotho, is a landlocked country in Southern Africa entirely surrounded by South Africa. It is the largest of the world's three sovereign enclaves, states completely encircled by a single other country. The kingdom lies within the Maloti Mountains and contains the highest peak in southern Africa. Its capital and largest city is Maseru. Its elevated terrain gives it a distinctive highland character within the region.",
  "liberia": "Liberia, officially the Republic of Liberia, is a country on the West African coast. It is bordered by Sierra Leone to the northwest, Guinea to the north, Ivory Coast to the east, and the Atlantic Ocean to the south and southwest. The official language is English, though over twenty indigenous languages are spoken, reflecting the country's ethnic and cultural diversity. Its capital and largest city is Monrovia. The country's position along the Atlantic seaboard has shaped its role in West Africa.",
  "libya": "Libya, officially the State of Libya, is a country in the Maghreb region of North Africa. It borders the Mediterranean Sea to the north, Egypt to the east, Sudan to the southeast, Chad to the south, Niger to the southwest, Algeria to the west, and Tunisia to the northwest. It is among the largest countries in Africa and the Arab world by area. The country maintains a territorial claim to an area of southeastern Algeria, south of the Libyan town of Ghat. Its capital and largest city is Tripoli, located in the northwest along the Mediterranean coast.",
  "liechtenstein": "Liechtenstein, officially the Principality of Liechtenstein, is a doubly landlocked microstate in the Central European Alps. It lies between Austria to the east and northeast and Switzerland to the north, west, and south. Formed in 1719, it became fully independent upon the dissolution of the German Confederation in 1866. The state is a monarchy headed by the reigning prince of Liechtenstein. Its Alpine setting and small size have shaped its identity as one of Europe's smallest sovereign states.",
  "lithuania": "Lithuania, officially the Republic of Lithuania, is a country in the Baltic region of Europe. It is one of the three Baltic states and lies on the eastern shore of the Baltic Sea, bordered by Latvia to the north, Belarus to the east and south, Poland to the south, and the Russian exclave of Kaliningrad Oblast to the southwest, with a maritime border with Sweden to the west. Its capital and largest city is Vilnius, while other major cities include Kaunas, Klaipėda, Šiauliai, and Panevėžys. Lithuanians are the titular nation and belong to the Baltic ethnolinguistic group. They speak Lithuanian, the country's national language.",
  "lozi": "The Lozi kingdom, also known as Barotseland or Bulozi, was a Central African state of the Lozi people (formerly called the Luyana) centered on the Barotse Floodplain of the upper Zambezi River in what is now western Zambia. Founded around the seventeenth century by settlers whose ruling dynasty traced its origins to the Lunda region, it was headed by a king titled the Litunga and grew into a substantial power through conquest, tribute, and control of the fertile flood-plain lands. Its society was shaped by the annual flooding of the Zambezi, most famously expressed in the Kuomboka ceremony, in which the Litunga and his people move from the inundated plain to higher ground. In the 1840s the kingdom was overrun by the Kololo, a Sotho-speaking group from the south, until a Lozi rebellion restored the indigenous monarchy in 1864. Under Litunga Lewanika in the late nineteenth century it entered treaties with the British South Africa Company, coming under British protection within what became Northern Rhodesia while the Lozi monarchy retained considerable internal authority.",
  "luba": "The Luba Empire was a Central African state that arose in the savanna and marshy grasslands around the Upemba Depression, in the region of the present-day southern Democratic Republic of the Congo. Its Bantu-speaking people were ruled by a sacred king who bore the title Mulopwe, and tradition traced the royal line to the hunter-hero Kalala Ilunga, who was said to have overthrown the earlier ruler Kongolo Mwamba. Growing out of communities skilled in ironworking, fishing, and farming, the kingdom drew its power from control of trade in salt, copper, and iron and from a tribute system that redistributed resources among a class of nobles. At its height in the eighteenth and nineteenth centuries it extended its influence across a wide region through vassal tributary chiefdoms and shaped political models later adopted by neighbouring peoples. The empire declined amid nineteenth-century disruption from the East African slave and ivory trade and a succession dispute, and its lands were ultimately absorbed into the Congo Free State.",
  "lunda": "The Lunda Empire was a Central African state that flourished from the 17th to the 19th centuries in the savanna region spanning present-day Democratic Republic of the Congo, Angola, and Zambia. Its paramount ruler bore the title Mwata Yamvo and headed a hierarchical system of subordinate chiefs, a political model whose institutions spread to influence neighboring peoples. The empire grew wealthy through long-distance trade, exchanging ivory and captives for cloth, guns, and other goods with both Portuguese traders on the Atlantic coast and merchants linked to the Indian Ocean. At its height it controlled an extensive territory and stood among the larger of the Bantu-speaking states of central Africa. In the later 19th century it fragmented under internal strain and external pressure, including Chokwe incursions, before its lands were partitioned among the Congo Free State, Portuguese Angola, and British-administered territory.",
  "luxembourg": "Luxembourg, officially the Grand Duchy of Luxembourg, is a landlocked country in Western Europe. It is bordered by Belgium to the west and north, Germany to the east, and France to the south and west. Its capital and most populous city, Luxembourg City, is one of the four institutional seats of the European Union and hosts several EU institutions, notably the Court of Justice of the European Union, the highest judicial authority in the EU. As part of the Low Countries, Luxembourg has close historic, political, and cultural ties to Belgium and the Netherlands. Its status as a grand duchy and its central location give it a distinctive place among European states.",
  "macao": "Macau, also spelled Macao, is a special administrative region of China. It comprises the Macau Peninsula together with the islands of Taipa and Coloane and the reclaimed Cotai zone between them, along with several smaller islets. It borders Zhuhai to the north and west and lies west of Hong Kong, separated by the Pearl River estuary. Formerly a Portuguese colony, the territory was first leased to Portugal by the Ming dynasty as a trading post in 1557, giving it a long Luso-Chinese heritage. Densely populated, Macau blends Portuguese and Chinese influences in its culture and administration.",
  "madagascar": "Madagascar, officially the Republic of Madagascar, is an island country in the Indian Ocean lying off the southeastern coast of Africa. It comprises the island of Madagascar, one of the world's largest, together with numerous smaller peripheral islands. Its capital and largest city is Antananarivo. Following the breakup of the supercontinent Gondwana, Madagascar split from Africa during the Early Jurassic period and later separated from the Indian subcontinent, leaving it long isolated. This isolation allowed its native plants and animals to evolve in relative seclusion, giving the island exceptional biological distinctiveness.",
  "malawi": "Malawi, officially the Republic of Malawi, is a landlocked country in Southeast Africa. It is bordered by Zambia to the west, Tanzania to the north and northeast, and Mozambique to the east, south, and southwest. Lilongwe is its capital and largest city. The region now known as Malawi was settled around the 10th century by early inhabitants including the Akafula, also known as the Abathwa. Its history and geography have long shaped life across this part of the African interior.",
  "malaya": "Malaya, also called British Malaya, is the historical term for the Malay Peninsula and the network of British colonies and protectorates established there, in what is today Peninsular Malaysia and Singapore. Rather than a single unified state, it consisted of the Straits Settlements, a British crown colony that included Penang, Malacca, and Singapore, alongside a set of Malay sultanates that came under British protection while retaining their own hereditary rulers. From 1896 four of these states, Perak, Selangor, Negeri Sembilan, and Pahang, were grouped as the Federated Malay States under a British Resident-General, while others, such as Johor, Kedah, Kelantan, Terengganu, and Perlis, later formed the more autonomous Unfederated Malay States. British control brought large-scale tin mining and rubber plantation economies, drawing substantial Chinese and Indian immigrant labor that reshaped the peninsula's population. After the Second World War these territories were reorganized into the Malayan Union and then the Federation of Malaya, which gained independence in 1957 and became the core of modern Malaysia.",
  "malaysia": "Malaysia is a country in Southeast Asia and a federal constitutional monarchy. It consists of thirteen states and three federal territories, separated by the South China Sea into two regions: Peninsular Malaysia on the mainland and East Malaysia on the island of Borneo. Peninsular Malaysia shares land and maritime borders with Thailand, along with maritime borders with Singapore, Vietnam, and Indonesia, while East Malaysia shares land borders with Brunei and Indonesia. Kuala Lumpur is the national capital, largest city, and seat of the legislature, while Putrajaya serves as the federal administrative capital housing the executive and judicial branches. Straddling both mainland and maritime Southeast Asia, Malaysia spans two distinct regions.",
  "maldives": "The Maldives, officially the Republic of Maldives and historically known as the Maldive Islands, is an archipelagic country in South Asia. It lies in the Indian Ocean near the southeastern boundary of the Arabian Sea, southwest of India and Sri Lanka. Its chain of 26 atolls stretches across the equator from Ihavandhippolhu Atoll in the north to Addu Atoll in the south. Although its land is minimal, it is scattered across a vast expanse of sea, making it one of the world's most spatially dispersed sovereign states. Built from atolls, the Maldives is renowned for its dispersed island geography.",
  "mali": "Mali, officially the Republic of Mali, is a landlocked country in West Africa and one of the largest states on the continent. It is bordered by Algeria to the north, Niger to the east, Mauritania to the northwest, Burkina Faso and Ivory Coast to the south, and Guinea and Senegal to the west. Its capital and largest city is Bamako. It ranks among the largest countries both in Africa and in the world by area. A significant share of its population is young, with a large proportion estimated to be under the age of fifteen.",
  "malta": "Malta, officially the Republic of Malta, is an island country of Southern Europe located in the Mediterranean Sea between Sicily and North Africa. It consists of an archipelago lying south of Italy, east of Tunisia, and north of Libya. The two official languages are Maltese and English, with Maltese recognised as the national language. The country's capital is Valletta, among the smallest capital cities in the European Union. Densely populated for its size, Malta ranks among the world's smallest and most crowded countries.",
  "qing dynasty": "The Qing dynasty was the last imperial dynasty of China, which ruled from the mid-seventeenth century until the early twentieth century. It was founded by the Manchus, a people descended from the Jurchens of the northeast whose rulers came from the Aisin-Gioro house, who overthrew the Ming and established a foreign conquest dynasty over China. Under emperors such as Kangxi, Yongzheng, and Qianlong the empire reached its height, expanding to incorporate Manchuria, Mongolia, Tibet, and Xinjiang and becoming one of the largest and most populous states in the world. The Qing governed a vast multiethnic realm through a dual system that preserved Manchu identity and privileges while adopting Chinese administrative and Confucian institutions. Weakened in the nineteenth century by internal rebellions and foreign pressure, the dynasty collapsed in the Xinhai Revolution, ending more than two millennia of imperial rule in China.",
  "marshall is.": "The Marshall Islands, officially the Republic of the Marshall Islands, is an archipelagic country in Oceania. The sovereign state lies west of the International Date Line and north of the equator in the Micronesia region of the Northwestern Pacific Ocean. Its territory consists of coral atolls and small islands divided across two chains, Ratak in the east and Ralik in the west. The overwhelming majority of its territory is lagoon waters, giving it one of the largest proportions of water to land of any sovereign state. It shares maritime boundaries with Wake Island, Kiribati, Nauru, and the Federated States of Micronesia.",
  "mauritania": "Mauritania, officially the Islamic Republic of Mauritania, is a country in the Maghreb region of West Africa. It is bordered by the Atlantic Ocean to the west, Western Sahara to the north and northwest, Algeria to the northeast, Mali to the east and southeast, and Senegal to the southwest. Much of its territory lies within the Sahara desert, and most of its population lives in the more temperate south. Its capital and largest city, Nouakchott, sits on the Atlantic coast. The country's name derives from Mauretania, the Latin name for a region in the ancient Maghreb.",
  "mauritius": "Mauritius, officially the Republic of Mauritius, is an island country in the Indian Ocean located off the southeastern coast of Africa, east of Madagascar. It includes the main island of Mauritius as well as Rodrigues, Agaléga, and St. Brandon. Together with Rodrigues and nearby Réunion, it forms part of the Mascarene Islands. The main island, where the population is concentrated, hosts the capital and largest city, Port Louis. The nation also holds a vast exclusive economic zone across the surrounding ocean, reflecting its dispersed island character.",
  "mbailundu": "Bailundo, known before 1975 as Vila Teixeira da Silva, is a municipality and town in the province of Huambo, Angola. It lies in the central highlands of the country and gives its name to the non-sovereign Kingdom of Bailundo, a traditional monarchy seated there. During the 1990s the town served as the location of the headquarters of the UNITA leader Jonas Savimbi. The kingship of Bailundo has continued as a customary institution into the present era, passing between traditional rulers. The area sits in a mountainous region near the city of Huambo and its airport.",
  "mexico": "Mexico, officially the United Mexican States, is a country in North America and the northernmost country in Latin America. It borders the United States to the north and Guatemala and Belize to the southeast, with maritime frontiers on the Pacific Ocean to the west, the Caribbean Sea to the southeast, and the Gulf of Mexico to the east. It ranks among the larger countries of the world by land area and is home to the largest population of native Spanish speakers. Mexico City is the capital and largest city, ranking among the most populous metropolitan areas in the world. It is one of the most populous countries in the world and one of the northernmost states of Latin America.",
  "micronesia": "Micronesia is a subregion of Oceania made up of roughly two thousand small islands scattered across the Northwestern Pacific Ocean. It shares a close cultural history with Maritime Southeast Asia to the west, Polynesia to the east, and Melanesia to the south, as well as with the wider community of Austronesian peoples. The region has a tropical marine climate and forms part of the Oceanian biogeographic realm. Its islands include four main archipelagos, the Caroline Islands, the Gilbert Islands, the Mariana Islands, and the Marshall Islands, along with many islands belonging to no archipelago. Political control across Micronesia varies from island to island and is distributed among several sovereign nations.",
  "moldova": "Moldova, officially the Republic of Moldova, is a landlocked country in Eastern Europe. It is bordered by Romania to the west and Ukraine to the north, east, and south, with the unrecognised breakaway region of Transnistria lying across the Dniester river along its eastern edge. It is a unitary parliamentary democratic republic whose capital and largest city, Chișinău, serves as its main cultural and commercial centre. Most of its territory belonged to the Principality of Moldavia from the 14th century until 1812. In that year the region was ceded to the Russian Empire by the Ottoman Empire, to which Moldavia had been a vassal, and became known as Bessarabia.",
  "monaco": "Monaco, officially the Principality of Monaco, is a sovereign city-state and microstate in Western Europe. Situated on the French Riviera, it forms a semi-enclave bordered by France to the north, east, and west, with the Mediterranean Sea to the south and the Italian region of Liguria a short distance to the east. It is among the smallest sovereign states in the world, ranking behind only Vatican City, and it is also the most densely populated. Monaco has the shortest national coastline of any non-landlocked country. Only a minority of its residents hold Monégasque nationality.",
  "mongolia": "Mongolia is a landlocked country in East Asia, bordered by Russia to the north and China to the south. It ranks among the largest countries in the world by area and is the second largest landlocked state after Kazakhstan, as well as the largest landlocked country that does not border an inland sea. It is one of the world's most sparsely populated sovereign states. Much of the country lies on the Mongolian Plateau, and its natural environment is defined by grassy steppe, mountains to the north and west, and the Gobi Desert to the south. Its only neighbours are Russia and China, giving it borders solely with those two states.",
  "montenegro": "Montenegro is a country in Southeast Europe, on the Balkan Peninsula. It is bordered by Serbia to the northeast, Bosnia and Herzegovina to the northwest, Kosovo to the east, Albania to the southeast, and Croatia to the west, and it has a coastline along the Adriatic Sea to the southwest. Its capital and largest city is Podgorica, while Cetinje serves as the Old Royal Capital and a cultural centre. Before the arrival of the Slavic peoples in the Balkans in the 6th and 7th centuries CE, the area now known as Montenegro was inhabited principally by peoples known as Illyrians. The country is divided administratively into a number of municipalities.",
  "montserrat": "Montserrat is a British Overseas Territory in the Caribbean. It forms part of the Leeward Islands, the northern portion of the Lesser Antilles chain of the West Indies. The island is a small landmass with a modest length, width, and coastline. It is nicknamed the Emerald Isle of the Caribbean, both for its resemblance to coastal Ireland and for the Irish ancestry of many of its inhabitants. Montserrat is the only non-fully-sovereign full member of the Caribbean Community and the Organisation of Eastern Caribbean States.",
  "morocco": "Morocco, officially the Kingdom of Morocco, is a country in the Maghreb region of North Africa. It has coastlines on the Mediterranean Sea to the north and the Atlantic Ocean to the west, and it borders Algeria to the east and the disputed territory of Western Sahara to the south, much of which it has occupied since 1975. Along its northern coast lie the Spanish exclaves of Ceuta, Melilla, and Peñón de Vélez de la Gomera, which Morocco claims together with several small Spanish-controlled islands. Its capital is Rabat, while its largest city is Casablanca. It also claims to share a border with Mauritania through the disputed territory of Western Sahara.",
  "mossi states": "The Mossi, also spelled Mosi, are a Gur ethnic group native to what is now Burkina Faso, concentrated primarily in the Volta River basin. They are the largest ethnic group in the country, forming a majority of its population. The remainder of Burkina Faso's people belong to more than sixty other ethnic groups, chiefly the Gurunsi, Gurma, Senufo, Lobi, Bobo, Bissa, and Fulani. The Mossi speak the Mòoré language. Their homeland lies chiefly in the Volta River basin of modern Burkina Faso.",
  "mozambique": "Mozambique, officially the Republic of Mozambique, is a country in Southeast Africa bordered by the Indian Ocean to the east, Tanzania to the north, Malawi and Zambia to the northwest, Zimbabwe to the west, and Eswatini and South Africa to the south and southwest. It is separated from the Comoros, Mayotte, and Madagascar by the Mozambique Channel to the east. Its capital and largest city is Maputo. Between the 7th and 11th centuries a series of Swahili port towns developed along the coast, contributing to a distinct Swahili culture and dialect. In the late medieval period these towns were frequented by traders from Somalia, Ethiopia, Egypt, Arabia, Persia, and India.",
  "myanmar": "Myanmar, officially the Republic of the Union of Myanmar and also known as Burma, is a country in the northwest of Southeast Asia. It is the largest country by area in Mainland Southeast Asia and is bordered by India and Bangladesh to the northwest, China to the northeast, Laos and Thailand to the east and southeast, and the Andaman Sea and the Bay of Bengal to the south and southwest. Its capital is Naypyidaw, while its largest city is Yangon, formerly known as Rangoon. Early civilisations in the region included the Tibeto-Burman-speaking Pyu city-states in Upper Myanmar and the Mon kingdoms in Lower Myanmar. Burma was the country's official English name until 1989.",
  "n. cyprus": "Northern Cyprus, officially the Turkish Republic of Northern Cyprus, is a de facto state comprising the northern third of the island of Cyprus. It is recognised only by Turkey, while the international community regards it as territory of the Republic of Cyprus under Turkish military occupation. Its terrain extends from Cape Apostolos Andreas at the tip of the Karpass Peninsula in the northeast to Morphou Bay in the northwest, with Cape Kormakitis as its westernmost point and the Kokkina exclave lying west of the mainland. A United Nations buffer zone separates the two sides of the island and runs through Nicosia, the island's largest city. Nicosia serves as the capital of both the northern and southern administrations.",
  "n. mariana is.": "The Northern Mariana Islands, officially the Commonwealth of the Northern Mariana Islands, is an unincorporated territory and commonwealth of the United States. It consists of the fourteen northern islands of the Mariana Archipelago in the northwestern Pacific Ocean, with the southernmost island, Guam, forming a separate U.S. territory. During the colonial period the islands were variously under the control of the Spanish, German, and Japanese empires. After World War II they were administered by the United States as part of the United Nations trust territories, having been listed by the United Nations as a non-self-governing territory until 1990. The islands formally joined the United States as a territory in 1986, with their population gaining United States citizenship.",
  "namibia": "Namibia, officially the Republic of Namibia, is a country in Southern Africa fronting the Atlantic Ocean along its western coast. It borders Angola and Zambia to the north, Botswana to the east, and South Africa to the south, and comes within a short distance of Zimbabwe along the Zambezi river in the northeast, near a quadripoint at Kazungula. Windhoek is its capital and largest city. Namibia is the driest country in sub-Saharan Africa. It has been inhabited since prehistoric times by the Khoi, San, Damara, and Nama peoples, with Bantu peoples arriving around the 14th century as part of the Bantu expansion.",
  "natal": "Natal was a British colony on the southeastern coast of Africa, in the region that is now the KwaZulu-Natal province of South Africa. It was proclaimed a British colony in 1843 after Britain annexed the short-lived Boer republic of Natalia, and its capital was established at Pietermaritzburg. Initially administered as an appendage of the Cape Colony, Natal became a separate crown colony in 1856 and was granted responsible self-government in 1893. Its economy centred on coastal sugar plantations worked from 1860 by large numbers of Indian indentured labourers, giving the colony a distinctive multi-ethnic population alongside its African majority and settler minority. Bordering the Zulu Kingdom, Natal was shaped by conflict with the Zulu and by the Second Boer War, and in 1910 it ceased to exist as a colony when it became a founding province of the Union of South Africa.",
  "nauru": "Nauru, officially the Republic of Nauru and formerly known as Pleasant Island, is an island country and microstate in the South Pacific Ocean. It lies within the Micronesia subregion of Oceania, with its nearest neighbour being Banaba, part of Kiribati, to the east. One of the smallest countries in the world, Nauru is also the smallest member state of the Commonwealth of Nations by both area and population. It is likewise among the least populous countries in the world, ranking near the very bottom by population. Nauru is a member of the United Nations, the Commonwealth of Nations, and the Organisation of African, Caribbean and Pacific States.",
  "ndebele": "The Ndebele kingdom, also known as Matabeleland or Mthwakazi, was a Southern African state founded in the early nineteenth century by Mzilikazi of the Khumalo clan, a leader of Nguni origin who broke from the Zulu ruler Shaka during the upheavals of the Mfecane. After migrating northward across the Transvaal and eventually the Limpopo River, his followers—the Ndebele or Matabele—settled in the southwestern part of present-day Zimbabwe, with their principal centre at Bulawayo. The kingdom was organized as a highly militarized society built around age-based regiments modelled on the Zulu system, and it incorporated conquered Sotho-Tswana and Shona peoples into a centralized, multi-ethnic state. Under Mzilikazi and his successor Lobengula, it dominated the surrounding region and exacted tribute from neighbouring communities. The kingdom fell to the British South Africa Company in the First Matabele War of 1893, after which its territory was absorbed into the colony of Southern Rhodesia.",
  "nepal": "Nepal, officially the Federal Democratic Republic of Nepal, is a landlocked country in South Asia. It is mainly situated in the Himalayas but also includes parts of the Indo-Gangetic Plain, bordering the Tibet Autonomous Region of China to the north and India to the south, east, and west. It is narrowly separated from Bangladesh by the Siliguri Corridor and from Bhutan by the Indian state of Sikkim. Nepal has a diverse geography ranging from fertile plains and subalpine forested hills to eight of the world's ten highest mountains, including Mount Everest, the highest point above mean sea level on Earth. Kathmandu is the nation's capital and its largest city.",
  "netherlands": "The Netherlands, informally known as Holland, is a country in Northwestern Europe with overseas territories in the Caribbean. It is the largest of the four constituent countries of the Kingdom of the Netherlands and consists of twelve provinces along with three overseas special municipalities. The European portion has land borders with Germany to the east and Belgium to the south, and a coastline along the North Sea to the north and west. It shares maritime borders with the United Kingdom, Germany, and Belgium in the North Sea. These maritime boundaries are set within that same body of water shared with its neighbours.",
  "netherlands antilles": "The Netherlands Antilles, also known as the Dutch Antilles, was a constituent Caribbean country of the Kingdom of the Netherlands. It comprised the islands of Saba, Sint Eustatius, and Sint Maarten in the Lesser Antilles, together with Aruba, Bonaire, and Curaçao in the Leeward Antilles. The country came into being in 1954 as the autonomous successor of the Dutch colony of Curaçao and Dependencies. It was gradually reshaped as Aruba, Sint Maarten, and Curaçao gained the status of constituent countries within the Kingdom. It was dissolved in 2010, with Saba, Sint Eustatius, and Bonaire becoming special municipalities of the Netherlands as the Caribbean Netherlands.",
  "netherlands indies": "The Dutch East Indies, also known as the Netherlands East Indies, was a Dutch colony whose territory largely corresponds to the modern state of Indonesia. It was formed from the nationalised trading posts of the Dutch East India Company, which came under the administration of the Dutch government in 1800. Through the Anglo-Dutch Treaty of 1824, the Dutch ceded the governorate of Dutch Malacca to Britain, an area later incorporated into modern Malaysia. During the 19th century the Dutch fought many wars against indigenous rulers and peoples across the archipelago. Indonesia declared independence in 1945, and after the Indonesian War of Independence the Netherlands recognized it in 1949.",
  "new caledonia": "New Caledonia is a French territory consisting of a group of islands in the southwest Pacific Ocean, lying southwest of Vanuatu and east of Australia. Located far from Metropolitan France, it forms a sui generis collectivity of the French Republic with a unique legal status enshrined in a dedicated chapter of the French Constitution. Part of the Melanesia subregion, the archipelago includes the main island of Grande Terre, the Loyalty Islands, the Chesterfield Islands, the Belep archipelago, the Isle of Pines, and various remote islets. The Chesterfield Islands lie within the Coral Sea. Grande Terre is affectionately nicknamed le Caillou by locals, a name often extended to New Caledonia as a whole.",
  "new zealand": "New Zealand is an island country in the southwestern Pacific Ocean, consisting of two main landmasses—the North Island (Te Ika-a-Māui) and the South Island (Te Waipounamu)—along with over 600 smaller islands. It lies east of Australia across the Tasman Sea and south of New Caledonia, Fiji, and Tonga. Its varied topography and sharp mountain peaks, including the Southern Alps (Kā Tiritiri o te Moana), owe much to tectonic uplift and volcanic eruptions. Wellington is the country's capital, while Auckland is its most populous city. It is the sixth-largest island country by area.",
  "nguni": "The Nguni are a cluster of closely related Bantu ethnic groups native to Southern Africa, forming one of the region's largest ethnolinguistic communities. They are traditionally divided into a northern branch, which includes the Zulu and the Swazi, and a southern branch, which includes the Xhosa along with related societies such as the Thembu and Mpondo, while the Ndebele are also counted among them. Their closely related tongues, the Nguni languages, are distinguished among Bantu languages by click consonants absorbed through contact and intermarriage with earlier Khoisan-speaking inhabitants. The ancestors of the Nguni settled the eastern regions of Southern Africa during the later Iron Age, developing societies based on cattle-keeping and cultivation. Today Nguni peoples are concentrated in South Africa, Eswatini, and Zimbabwe, where their languages and traditions remain a major part of the region's cultural identity.",
  "ngwato": "The Bamangwato, also known as the BaNgwato or Ngwato, are one of the eight principal Tswana chieftaincies of Botswana. The community is centred in the Central District, historically forming in the Serowe, Palapye, and Mahalapye area. Its main town and capital, established after 1902, is Serowe. The Bamangwato are led by a paramount chief who holds a hereditary position. That chief occupies one of the seats in the Ntlo ya Dikgosi, the national House of Chiefs.",
  "nicaragua": "Nicaragua, officially the Republic of Nicaragua, is the geographically largest country in Central America. It is bordered by Honduras to the north, the Caribbean Sea to the east, Costa Rica to the south, and the Pacific Ocean to the west, and also shares maritime borders with El Salvador and Colombia. It is among the more populous countries of Central America. Managua is the country's largest city and national capital, and ranks among the largest cities in Central America. It is the third-most populous country in Central America, after Guatemala and Honduras.",
  "niger": "Niger, officially the Republic of the Niger, is a landlocked country in West Africa. It is bordered by Libya to the northeast, Chad to the east, Nigeria to the south, Benin and Burkina Faso to the southwest, Mali to the west, and Algeria to the northwest. It is the largest landlocked country in West Africa, with the majority of its land area lying within the Sahara. Its predominantly Muslim population is concentrated mostly in clusters in the south and west of the country. It is also the second-largest landlocked nation in Africa, behind Chad.",
  "nigeria": "Nigeria, officially the Federal Republic of Nigeria, is a country in West Africa lying between the Sahel to the north and the Gulf of Guinea on the Atlantic Ocean to the south. It borders Niger to the north, Chad to the northeast, Cameroon to the east, and Benin to the west. The most populous country in Africa, it ranks among the most populous nations in the world. Nigeria is a federal republic composed of thirty-six states together with the Federal Capital Territory. Its capital is Abuja, located within that territory.",
  "niue": "Niue is a self-governing island country in free association with New Zealand, situated in the South Pacific Ocean. It forms part of Polynesia and is predominantly inhabited by Polynesians. One of the world's largest coral islands, it is nicknamed \"The Rock,\" derived from the traditional name \"Rock of Polynesia.\" Niue lies within a triangle formed by Tonga, Samoa, and the Cook Islands. It sits to the northeast of both New Zealand and Tonga.",
  "norfolk island": "Norfolk Island is an external territory of Australia located in the Pacific Ocean between New Zealand and New Caledonia, lying to the east of the Australian mainland. Together with the neighbouring Phillip Island and Nepean Island, the three collectively form the Territory of Norfolk Island. Its capital is Kingston. East Polynesians were the first to settle the island, but they had already departed before European arrival. Great Britain settled it as part of its 1788 colonisation of Australia.",
  "north korea": "North Korea, officially the Democratic People's Republic of Korea, is a country in East Asia occupying the northern half of the Korean Peninsula. It borders China and Russia to the north along the Yalu and Tumen rivers, and South Korea to the south at the Korean Demilitarized Zone. Its western border is formed by the Yellow Sea, while the Sea of Japan lies to the east. Pyongyang is the capital and largest city. The Korean Peninsula was first inhabited as early as the Lower Paleolithic period.",
  "north macedonia": "North Macedonia, officially the Republic of North Macedonia, is a landlocked country in Southeast Europe. It shares borders with Greece to the south, Albania to the west, Bulgaria to the east, Kosovo to the northwest, and Serbia to the north. The country constitutes roughly the northern third of the larger geographical region of Macedonia. Skopje is its capital and largest city, home to a substantial share of the national population. The majority of its residents are ethnic Macedonians, a South Slavic people.",
  "norway": "Norway, officially the Kingdom of Norway, is a Nordic country comprising the western and northernmost parts of the Scandinavian Peninsula in Northern Europe, along with the remote Arctic island of Jan Mayen and the archipelago of Svalbard. Bouvet Island, located in the Subantarctic, is a dependency rather than part of the Kingdom, and Norway also claims the Antarctic territories of Peter I Island and Queen Maud Land. Its capital and largest city is Oslo. The country shares a long eastern border with Sweden. It is bordered by Finland and Russia to the northeast.",
  "oman": "Oman, officially the Sultanate of Oman, is a country in the southeastern Arabian Peninsula in West Asia. It shares land borders with Saudi Arabia, the United Arab Emirates, and Yemen. Its coastline faces the Arabian Sea to the southeast and the Gulf of Oman to the northeast. The exclaves of Madha and Musandam are surrounded on their land borders by the United Arab Emirates, while Musandam's coast is defined by the Strait of Hormuz and the Gulf of Oman. Oman occupies a strategic position at the eastern edge of the Arabian Peninsula.",
  "opobo": "Opobo is a community and former city-state in Rivers State, in the South South region of Nigeria. It is divided into fourteen sections, known as \"polo.\" These sections are made up of sixty-seven war canoe houses. The fourteen sections are Adibie, Biriye, Diepiri, Dapu, Dappa Ye Amakiri, Epelle, and Fubarakworo. The remaining sections are Iroanya, Jaja, Kalaomuso, Ukonu, Kiepirima, Owujie, and Tolofari.",
  "orange free state": "The Orange Free State was a landlocked independent Boer republic in Southern Africa during the second half of the nineteenth century. It ceased to exist after being defeated and surrendering to the British Empire at the end of the Second Boer War in 1902. Extending between the Orange and Vaal rivers, its borders were determined by the United Kingdom in 1848, when the region was proclaimed as the Orange River Sovereignty, with a British Resident based in Bloemfontein. Bloemfontein and the southern parts of the territory had previously been settled by Griqua and by Trekboere from the Cape Colony. It is one of the three historical precursors to the present-day Free State province.",
  "ottoman empire": "The Ottoman Empire, historically also known as the Turkish Empire, was a state that spanned much of Southeast Europe, West Asia, and North Africa from the fourteenth century to the early twentieth century, centred in modern-day Turkey. It also controlled parts of southeastern Central Europe between the early sixteenth and early eighteenth centuries. The empire emerged from a principality founded in northwestern Anatolia around 1299 by the Turkoman tribal leader Osman I, whose successors conquered much of Anatolia and expanded into the Balkans by the mid-fourteenth century. The Ottomans ended the Byzantine Empire with the conquest of Constantinople in 1453 by Mehmed II. Further conquests by Selim I led the Sultans to adopt the title of caliph.",
  "ovimbundu": "The Ovimbundu, also known as the Southern Mbundu, are a Bantu ethnic group living on the Bié Plateau of central Angola and in the coastal strip west of these highlands. They are the largest ethnic group in Angola. The Ovimbundu overwhelmingly follow Christianity, mainly the Igreja Evangélica Congregacional de Angola, founded by American missionaries, and the Catholic Church. However, some still retain beliefs and practices drawn from African traditional religions. Their homeland forms a central highland region of the country.",
  "oyo": "The Oyo Empire was a Yoruba state centered in the northern savanna of Yorubaland, in what is now southwestern Nigeria. According to tradition it was founded by Oranmiyan, a prince linked to the sacred dynasty of Ile-Ife, and it rose to become the most powerful Yoruba polity. Its capital, Oyo-Ile (Old Oyo), was the seat of the Alaafin, the supreme ruler, whose authority was checked by a council of chiefs known as the Oyo Mesi led by the Bashorun. Exploiting open grasslands to build a formidable cavalry, Oyo dominated much of the region at its height in the seventeenth and eighteenth centuries, extending influence over neighbouring peoples and the kingdom of Dahomey. Weakened by internal disputes, the revolt of Ilorin, and the pressures of civil war, the empire collapsed in the early nineteenth century, giving way to successor states such as Ibadan.",
  "pakistan": "Pakistan, officially the Islamic Republic of Pakistan, is a country in South Asia. It is among the most populous countries in the world and has one of the largest Muslim populations of any nation. Islamabad is the capital, while Karachi is the largest city and financial centre. Bounded by the Arabian Sea to the south, the Gulf of Oman to the southwest, and the Sir Creek to the southeast, it shares land borders with India to the east, Afghanistan to the west, Iran to the southwest, and China to the northeast. It ranks among the larger countries in the world by area.",
  "palau": "Palau, officially the Republic of Palau, is an island country in the Micronesia subregion of Oceania in the western Pacific Ocean. It consists of roughly 340 islands and forms the western part of the Caroline Islands, while the eastern and central parts make up the Federated States of Micronesia. It ranks among the smallest countries in the world. The most populous island is Koror, home to the country's largest city of the same name. The capital, Ngerulmud, is located on the largest island of Babeldaob, in Melekeok State.",
  "palestine": "Palestine, officially the State of Palestine, is a country in the Southern Levant region of West Asia. It encompasses the West Bank, including East Jerusalem, and the Gaza Strip, both of which are occupied by Israel. These territories are collectively known as the Palestinian territories, or the occupied Palestinian territory. The West Bank also borders Jordan to the east, while the Gaza Strip borders Egypt to the southwest. Together the West Bank and the Gaza Strip make up the territory of the State of Palestine.",
  "panama": "Panama, officially the Republic of Panama, lies at the southern end of Central America in North America, bordering South America. It is bounded by Costa Rica to the west, Colombia to the southeast, the Caribbean Sea to the north, and the Pacific Ocean to the south. Its capital and largest city is Panama City, whose metropolitan area is home to a large share of the country's inhabitants. Before the arrival of Spanish colonists in the 16th century, the region was inhabited by a number of different Indigenous peoples. Panama broke away from Spain in 1821 and joined the Republic of Gran Colombia, a union of Nueva Granada, Ecuador, and Venezuela.",
  "papua new guinea": "Papua New Guinea, officially the Independent State of Papua New Guinea, is an island country in Oceania that comprises the eastern half of the island of New Guinea together with offshore islands in Melanesia, a region of the southwestern Pacific Ocean north of Australia. It has a land border with Indonesia to the west and maritime borders with Australia to the south and the Solomon Islands to the east. Its capital is Port Moresby, and the country includes a large mainland along with hundreds of islands. The eastern half of New Guinea was divided in 1884 between German New Guinea in the north and British New Guinea in the south. The latter was ceded to Australia in 1902 and reorganised as the Territory of Papua.",
  "paraguay": "Paraguay, officially the Republic of Paraguay, is a landlocked country in the central region of South America. It borders Bolivia to the northwest and north, Brazil to the northeast and east, and Argentina to the southeast, south, and west. Despite being landlocked, it has access to the Atlantic Ocean via the Paraná–Paraguay Waterway. The country is governed as a unitary presidential republic composed of a capital district and seventeen departments. Its capital and largest city is Asunción.",
  "persia": "Persia, known in the modern era as Iran and officially the Islamic Republic of Iran, is a country in West Asia. It borders Iraq to the west, Turkey, Azerbaijan, and Armenia to the northwest, the Caspian Sea to the north, Turkmenistan to the northeast, Afghanistan to the east, Pakistan to the southeast, and the Gulf of Oman and the Persian Gulf to the south. It ranks among the largest countries in the world by geographic size and is divided administratively into provinces. Tehran is the nation's capital and largest city and serves as its primary economic centre. The country was historically known as Persia.",
  "peru": "Peru, officially the Republic of Peru, is a country in western South America. It is bordered to the north by Ecuador and Colombia, to the east by Brazil, to the southeast by Bolivia, to the south by Chile, and to the south and west by the Pacific Ocean. Peru is a megadiverse country, with habitats ranging from the arid plains of the Pacific coastal region in the west, to the peaks of the Andes mountains extending from the north to the southeast, to the tropical Amazon basin rainforest in the east drained by the Amazon River. Its capital and largest city is Lima. It is among the largest countries in South America.",
  "philippines": "The Philippines, officially the Republic of the Philippines, is an archipelagic country in Southeast Asia located in the western Pacific Ocean. It consists of thousands of islands, broadly categorized into three main geographical divisions from north to south: Luzon, Visayas, and Mindanao. The country is bounded by the South China Sea to the west, the Philippine Sea to the east, and the Celebes Sea to the south. It shares maritime borders with Taiwan to the north, Japan to the northeast, Palau to the east and southeast, Indonesia to the south, Malaysia to the southwest, Vietnam to the west, and China to the northwest. It is one of the most populous countries in the world.",
  "pitcairn is.": "The Pitcairn Islands, officially Pitcairn, Henderson, Ducie and Oeno Islands, are a group of four volcanic islands in the southern Pacific Ocean. They form the sole British Overseas Territory in the Pacific Ocean. The four islands are scattered across several hundred kilometres of ocean, and Henderson Island accounts for the great majority of the land area, though only Pitcairn Island is inhabited. The nearest inhabited islands are Mangareva, part of French Polynesia, to the west, and Easter Island to the east. The islands are remote and sparsely populated, with a very small resident community.",
  "poland": "Poland, officially the Republic of Poland, is a country in Central Europe. It extends from the Baltic Sea in the north to the Sudetes and Carpathian Mountains in the south, and borders Lithuania and Russia to the northeast, Belarus and Ukraine to the east, Slovakia and the Czech Republic to the south, and Germany to the west. The territory has a varied landscape, diverse ecosystems, and a temperate climate. Poland is composed of sixteen voivodeships and is one of the more populous member states of the European Union. Its capital and largest city is Warsaw, while other major cities include Kraków, Wrocław, Łódź, Poznań, and Gdańsk.",
  "portugal": "Portugal, officially the Portuguese Republic, is a country in Southwestern Europe. It is a unitary republic comprising mainland Portugal on the southwestern Iberian Peninsula, bordered by Spain to the north and east, together with the Atlantic archipelagos of Madeira and the Azores. Lisbon is its capital and largest city. Portugal's internal waters and territorial sea account for a large share of its territory, and its exclusive economic zone is one of Europe's largest, while its terrain contains a diverse range of landscapes and regional climates. The western Iberian Peninsula has been inhabited since prehistory, with the earliest signs of settlement dating to the sixth millennium BC.",
  "portuguese east africa": "Portuguese Mozambique, also known as Portuguese East Africa, was the name by which Mozambique was designated during the period in which it was a Portuguese overseas territory. It originally constituted a string of Portuguese possessions along the south-east African coast, and later became a unified province, which now forms the Republic of Mozambique. Portuguese trading settlements, and later territories, were formed along the coast and into the Zambezi basin from 1498, when Vasco da Gama first reached the Mozambican coast. Lourenço Marques explored the area that is now Maputo Bay in 1544. The territory remained under Portuguese control until Mozambique achieved independence.",
  "portuguese guinea": "Portuguese Guinea was a Portuguese overseas territory in West Africa. It was known as the Overseas Province of Guinea from 1951 until 1972, and then as the State of Guinea from 1972 until 1974. Portugal held the territory from 1588 until 1974. It gained independence in September 1974 as the country of Guinea-Bissau. The territory lay in West Africa and formed part of Portugal's colonial holdings in the region.",
  "puerto rico": "Puerto Rico, officially the Commonwealth of Puerto Rico, is a self-governing Caribbean archipelago and island organized as an unincorporated territory of the United States under the designation of commonwealth. Located southeast of Florida, it lies between the Dominican Republic in the Greater Antilles and the U.S. Virgin Islands in the Lesser Antilles. It consists of the main island and numerous smaller islands, including Vieques, Culebra, and Mona. It is divided into municipalities, of which the most populous is the capital, San Juan. Spanish and English are the official languages of the government, though Spanish predominates.",
  "qatar": "Qatar, officially the State of Qatar, is a country in West Asia. It occupies the Qatar Peninsula on the northeastern coast of the Arabian Peninsula in the Middle East, sharing its sole land border with Saudi Arabia to the south, with the rest of its territory surrounded by the Persian Gulf. The Gulf of Bahrain, an inlet of the Persian Gulf, separates Qatar from nearby Bahrain. The capital is Doha, home to the great majority of the country's inhabitants. Most of the land area is made up of flat, low-lying desert.",
  "rapa nui": "Rapa Nui, also known as Easter Island, is an island and special territory of Chile in the southeastern Pacific Ocean. It lies at the southeasternmost point of the Polynesian Triangle in Oceania. The island is renowned for its monumental stone statues, called moai, which were carved by the early Rapa Nui people. Much of the island is protected within Rapa Nui National Park, and UNESCO named it a World Heritage Site. It is the only territory in Polynesia where Spanish is an official language, and experts still differ on when its Polynesian inhabitants first arrived.",
  "rattanakosin kingdom": "The Rattanakosin Kingdom, also known as the Kingdom of Siam after 1855, was the Siamese kingdom occupying the territory of modern-day Thailand. It was founded in 1782 with the establishment of Rattanakosin, or Bangkok, which replaced Thonburi as the capital of Siam. The kingdom governed through the mandala system. This arrangement allowed high local autonomy while the central kingdom effectively ruled over its wider area of suzerainty. The era spanned from the founding of the new capital until the Siamese revolution of 1932.",
  "romania": "Romania is a country in Southeast and Central Europe, lying on the lower course of the Danube and the northwestern shore of the Black Sea. It sits north of the Balkan Peninsula and borders Ukraine, Hungary, Serbia, Bulgaria, and Moldova. It is one of the larger countries of Europe by area and a member state of the European Union. The capital, largest city, and economic centre is Bucharest. It meets the Black Sea along its southeastern edge.",
  "russia": "Russia, or the Russian Federation, is a country spanning Eastern Europe and North Asia. It is the largest country in the world by area, extending across eleven time zones and sharing land borders with fourteen countries. It is the most populous country in Europe and a highly urbanised society. Moscow is the capital and largest city, ranking as Europe's most populous metropolitan area, while Saint Petersburg is the second-largest city and a major cultural centre. Its territory reaches across two continents.",
  "russian empire": "The Russian Empire was the final period of the Russian monarchy, spanning most of northern Eurasia from its establishment in 1721 until the proclamation of the Russian Republic in 1917. At its height in the late 19th century it was one of the largest empires in history, covering roughly one-sixth of the world's landmass. It also colonized Alaska before selling the territory in 1867. The empire conducted a single census, in 1897, which revealed a population of great ethnic, linguistic, religious, and socioeconomic diversity. It ranked among the largest empires ever, behind only the British and Mongol empires.",
  "rwanda": "Rwanda, officially the Republic of Rwanda, is a landlocked country in East Africa. Known as the \"Land of a Thousand Hills\" for its high elevation and rolling terrain, its geography is dominated by mountains in the west and savanna in the southeast. Its most notable lakes lie mainly in the western and northern regions, and several volcanoes of the Virunga chain rise in the northwest. The climate is a tropical highland one, with two rainy seasons and two dry seasons each year. Its capital and largest city is Kigali, located at the centre of the country and set at high altitude.",
  "s. geo. and the is.": "South Georgia and the South Sandwich Islands is a British Overseas Territory in the southern Atlantic Ocean. It is a remote and inhospitable collection of islands, consisting of South Georgia and a chain of smaller islands known as the South Sandwich Islands. South Georgia is by far the largest island in the territory. The South Sandwich Islands lie several hundred kilometres to its southeast. Together they make up a small and isolated total land area.",
  "s. sudan": "South Sudan, officially the Republic of South Sudan, is a landlocked country in East Africa. It is bordered by Sudan to the north, Ethiopia to the east, Kenya, Uganda, and the Democratic Republic of the Congo to the south, and the Central African Republic to the west. Its diverse landscape includes vast plains and plateaus, dry and tropical savannahs, inland floodplains, and forested mountains. The Nile River system is the defining physical feature of the country, running south to north across its center. Much of that centre is dominated by a large swamp known as the Sudd.",
  "saint barthelemy": "Saint Barthélemy, officially the Territorial Collectivity of Saint Barthélemy, is an overseas collectivity of France in the Caribbean. The island lies southeast of Saint Martin and north of the independent country of Saint Kitts and Nevis. It is situated northeast of the Dutch islands of Saba and Sint Eustatius. For many years the island was a French commune forming part of Guadeloupe, an overseas region and department of France. In 2003 its inhabitants voted in favour of secession from Guadeloupe to form a separate overseas collectivity of France.",
  "saint helena": "Saint Helena is a volcanic tropical island located in the South Atlantic Ocean, west of Africa. Its nearest countries geographically are Angola and Namibia. The island lies far out in the ocean, thousands of kilometres from the coast of Brazil to its west. It forms one of the three constituent parts of Saint Helena, Ascension and Tristan da Cunha, a British overseas territory. The island is small and rugged, reflecting its volcanic origins.",
  "saint kitts and nevis": "Saint Kitts and Nevis, officially the Federation of Saint Christopher and Nevis, is an island country in the Caribbean. It consists of the two islands of Saint Kitts and Nevis, in the Leeward Islands chain of the Lesser Antilles. It is among the smallest sovereign states in the Western Hemisphere and is the world's smallest sovereign federation. The country is a Commonwealth realm, recognising the British monarch as head of state. The capital is Basseterre, on the larger island of Saint Kitts, which also serves as the main port for passenger and cargo entry.",
  "saint lucia": "Saint Lucia is an island country in the eastern and southern Caribbean. Part of the Windward Islands of the Lesser Antilles, it lies north of Saint Vincent, northwest of Barbados, and south of Martinique. The nation's capital and largest city is Castries. The first proven inhabitants of the island are believed to have been the Arawaks. They are thought to have settled there in the early centuries AD.",
  "saint martin": "Saint Martin is an island in the Leeward Islands of the Lesser Antilles, in the northeastern Caribbean Sea east of Puerto Rico. It has been divided between France and the Netherlands since the Treaty of Concordia of 1648, making it one of the smallest inhabited land masses in the world shared by two sovereign powers. The larger northern portion is French, while the smaller southern portion, known as Sint Maarten, is Dutch, and the boundary between them has long remained open and freely crossable. The island's terrain is marked by low volcanic hills, salt ponds, and lagoons, and its economy historically rested on salt harvesting and small-scale agriculture before shifting toward tourism. Long shaped by European colonial rivalry and a Creole-speaking population of mixed African and European descent, Saint Martin retains a dual cultural and administrative character rooted in its French and Dutch heritage.",
  "samoa": "Samoa, officially the Independent State of Samoa, is an island country in Polynesia, part of Oceania in the South Pacific Ocean. It consists of two main islands, Savai'i and Upolu, two smaller inhabited islands, and several uninhabited islets. The country lies west of American Samoa, northeast of Tonga and Fiji, and within the broader Polynesian region of the Pacific. The capital and largest city is Apia, located on the island of Upolu. Its outlying islets include the Aleipata group off Upolu's eastern end.",
  "san marino": "San Marino, officially the Republic of San Marino, is a landlocked microstate in Southern Europe completely surrounded by Italy. It lies on the northeastern slopes of the Apennine Mountains and is one of two microstates within the Italian Peninsula, the other being Vatican City. Its capital, the City of San Marino, sits atop Monte Titano, while its largest settlement is Dogana in the municipality of Serravalle. San Marino claims to have been founded in AD 301, and it presents itself as the oldest extant sovereign state. It also claims the distinction of being the world's oldest constitutional republic.",
  "saudi arabia": "Saudi Arabia, officially the Kingdom of Saudi Arabia, is a country in West Asia occupying the bulk of the Arabian Peninsula at the centre of the Middle East. It is the largest country in the Middle East and one of the largest in Asia, bordered by the Red Sea to the west and by Jordan, Iraq, and Kuwait to the north. To the east lie the Persian Gulf, Bahrain, Qatar, and the United Arab Emirates, with Oman to the southeast and Yemen to the south. The Gulf of Aqaba in the northwest separates it from Egypt and Israel, and it is the only country with a coastline along both the Red Sea and the Arabian Gulf. Most of its terrain consists of arid desert, lowland, steppe, and mountains.",
  "scarborough reef": "Scarborough Shoal, also known as Bajo de Masinloc, Huangyan Island, and Panatag Shoal, is a coral atoll and reef with an inner lagoon and several rocks that stand above high tide. It lies between Macclesfield Bank to the west and the island of Luzon to the east. Luzon, roughly 220 kilometres away, is the nearest landmass to the shoal. The atoll is a disputed territory, claimed simultaneously by the People's Republic of China, the Republic of China, and the Republic of the Philippines. Its status as a claimed feature has kept it contested among those three governments.",
  "senegal": "Senegal, officially the Republic of Senegal, is the westernmost country of mainland West Africa, situated along the Atlantic Ocean coast. It borders Mauritania to the north, Mali to the east, Guinea to the southeast, and Guinea-Bissau to the southwest. Senegal nearly surrounds the Gambia, a country occupying a narrow strip of land along the Gambia River that separates the southern region of Casamance from the rest of the country. It also shares a maritime border with Cape Verde in the Atlantic. The capital and largest city of Senegal is Dakar.",
  "serbia": "Serbia, officially the Republic of Serbia, is a landlocked country in Southeast and Central Europe located in the Balkans. It is bordered by Hungary to the north, Romania to the northeast, Bulgaria to the southeast, and North Macedonia to the south. To the west it adjoins Croatia, Bosnia and Herzegovina, and Montenegro, and it also claims a border with Albania through the disputed territory of Kosovo. Belgrade, the country's capital, is also its largest city. Serbia lies within the Balkans at the meeting of Southeast and Central Europe.",
  "serranilla bank": "Serranilla Bank is a partially submerged reef with small uninhabited islets in the western Caribbean Sea. It lies northeast of the Punta Gorda River in Nicaragua and southwest of Jamaica. Its closest neighbouring land feature is Bajo Nuevo Bank, situated to the east. Serranilla Bank was first depicted on Spanish maps in 1510. It is administered by Colombia as part of the department of San Andrés and Providencia.",
  "seychelles": "Seychelles, officially the Republic of Seychelles, is an archipelagic country consisting of 115 islands in the Indian Ocean. Its capital and largest city, Victoria, lies east of mainland Africa. Nearby island countries and territories include the Maldives, Comoros, Madagascar, Mauritius, and the French overseas departments of Mayotte and Réunion to the south, along with the Chagos Archipelago to the east. It is among the smallest and least populous of Africa's sovereign states. The Seychelles archipelago was uninhabited prior to sustained external contact.",
  "shona": "Shona most commonly refers to the Shona people, a Southern African ethnic group, and to the Shona language, a Bantu language they speak. The term is also applied to the wider Shona group of languages defined in the early twentieth century. It is historically associated with the Kingdom of Zimbabwe, a Shona state that flourished from the thirteenth to the fifteenth centuries. The name additionally attaches to various other things, including a given name and geographical features such as the Shona hotspot in the Atlantic Ocean. As a label, Shona thus spans a people, their languages, and their historical polities in Southern Africa.",
  "siachen glacier": "The Siachen Glacier is a glacier in the eastern Karakoram range of the Himalayas, lying just northeast of the point where the Line of Control between India and Pakistan ends in northeastern Kashmir. It is the longest glacier in the Karakoram and the second-longest in the world's non-polar regions. The glacier descends from its head at Indira Col on the India–China border down to its terminus at a much lower altitude. Its remote, high-altitude terrain includes numerous major mountain passes. The entire glacier has been under the administration of India as part of the union territory of Ladakh since 1984.",
  "sierra leone": "Sierra Leone, officially the Republic of Sierra Leone, is a country on the west coast of West Africa. It is bordered to the southeast by Liberia and to the north by Guinea. The country has a tropical climate, with environments ranging from savannahs to rainforests. Its landscapes span a range of natural settings across this territory. Sierra Leone thus combines a West African coastal position with varied tropical environments.",
  "singapore": "Singapore, officially the Republic of Singapore, is an island country in Southeast Asia. Its territory comprises a main island, dozens of smaller satellite islands and islets, and one outlying islet. Lying just north of the equator off the southern tip of the Malay Peninsula, it borders the Strait of Malacca to the west, the Singapore Strait and Indonesia's Riau Islands to the south, the South China Sea to the east, and the Straits of Johor and the Malaysian state of Johor to the north. In its early history, Singapore was a maritime emporium known as Temasek. It later became a major constituent of several successive maritime empires.",
  "sint maarten": "Sint Maarten is a constituent country of the Kingdom of the Netherlands located in the Caribbean region of North America. It occupies the southern portion of the divided island of Saint Martin, while the northern portion constitutes the French overseas collectivity of Saint Martin. Its capital is Philipsburg. Together with the other Dutch islands in the Caribbean, Sint Maarten is often referred to as part of the Dutch Caribbean. The island's split between Dutch and French administration is a longstanding feature of its identity.",
  "slovakia": "Slovakia, officially the Slovak Republic, is a landlocked country in Central Europe. It is bordered by Poland to the north, Ukraine to the east, Hungary to the south, Austria to the west, and the Czech Republic to the northwest. Its territory is mostly mountainous. The capital and largest city is Bratislava, while the second largest city is Košice. The Slavs arrived in the territory of present-day Slovakia in the fifth and sixth centuries.",
  "slovenia": "Slovenia, officially the Republic of Slovenia, is a country in Central Europe. It borders Italy to the west, Austria to the north, Hungary to the northeast, and Croatia to the south and southeast, while its southwestern boundary features a short coastline on the Adriatic Sea. The country is mostly mountainous and forested, with terrain shaped by the Julian Alps and other ranges. Slovene is the official language. Slovenia has a predominantly temperate continental climate, apart from the Slovene Littoral and the Julian Alps.",
  "sokoto caliphate": "The Sokoto Caliphate, also known as the Sultanate of Sokoto, was a Sunni Muslim caliphate in West Africa. It was founded by Usman dan Fodio in 1804 during the Fulani jihads, after his victory over the Hausa Kingdoms in the Fulani War. At its height its territory extended across lands now part of present-day Cameroon, Burkina Faso, Niger, and Nigeria. It became the most populous empire in West Africa. The caliphate was dissolved after 1903, when British, French, and German forces conquered the region and partitioned it among their colonial holdings.",
  "solomon is.": "Solomon Islands, also known simply as the Solomons, is an archipelagic country in Melanesia, in the southwestern Pacific to the north-east of Australia. It comprises six major islands and over a thousand smaller ones scattered across the ocean. It lies near Bougainville to the west, New Caledonia and Vanuatu to the south-east, Fiji and Tuvalu to the east, and the Federated States of Micronesia and Nauru to the north. Its capital and largest city, Honiara, sits on Guadalcanal, the largest island. The country is part of the wider Oceania region and shares deep cultural and geographic ties with its Melanesian neighbours.",
  "somalia": "Somalia, officially the Federal Republic of Somalia, is the easternmost country in continental Africa. Stretching across the Horn of Africa, it borders Ethiopia to the west, Djibouti to the northwest, and Kenya to the southwest, with the Gulf of Aden to the north and the Indian Ocean to the east. It has the longest coastline on Africa's mainland. Its capital and largest city is Mogadishu. Somalia is among Africa's most ethnically homogeneous countries, with ethnic Somalis forming the great majority of its residents.",
  "somaliland": "Somaliland, officially the Republic of Somaliland, is a partially recognised state in the Horn of Africa. It lies on the southern coast of the Gulf of Aden and is bordered by Djibouti to the northwest, Ethiopia to the south and west, and Somalia to the east. Its capital and largest city is Hargeisa. Various Somali Muslim kingdoms were established in the area during the early Islamic period, including the Zeila-based Adal Sultanate in the 14th and 15th centuries. The territory has a distinct political history and claims the status of an independent republic.",
  "south africa": "South Africa, officially the Republic of South Africa, is the southernmost country in Africa. Its nine provinces are bounded to the south by a long coastline stretching along the South Atlantic and Indian Oceans, and to the north by Namibia, Botswana, and Zimbabwe, with Mozambique and Eswatini to the east and northeast; it entirely encloses Lesotho. It is unusual in having three capitals: Pretoria as the administrative capital, Cape Town as the legislative capital and seat of Parliament, and Bloemfontein as the judicial capital. Cape Town lies at the country's southwestern tip and is home to the national Parliament. South Africa is one of the most populous and economically significant countries on the continent.",
  "south korea": "South Korea, officially the Republic of Korea, is a country in East Asia occupying the southern half of the Korean Peninsula. It borders North Korea along the Korean Demilitarized Zone, with the Yellow Sea to the west and the Sea of Japan to the east. It claims to be the sole legitimate government of the entire peninsula and its adjacent islands. Its capital, Seoul, anchors a vast metropolitan area that holds a large share of the national population, with Busan, Daegu, and Incheon among other major cities. The Korean Peninsula has been inhabited since the Lower Paleolithic period and has a long, continuous cultural history.",
  "southern patagonian ice field": "The Southern Patagonian Ice Field, known in Spanish as Campo de Hielo Patagónico Sur, lies along the Southern Patagonian Andes on the border between Chile and Argentina. It is the world's second-largest contiguous extrapolar ice field. It is the larger of two surviving remnants of the Patagonian Ice Sheet, which once covered much of southern Chile during the last glacial period. That glaciation is known locally as the Llanquihue glaciation. The ice field remains a major feature of the high southern Andes.",
  "spain": "Spain, officially the Kingdom of Spain, is a country in Southern and Western Europe with additional territories in North Africa. It occupies most of the Iberian Peninsula and is the largest country in Southern Europe. Its territory also includes the Canary Islands in the eastern Atlantic, the Balearic Islands in the western Mediterranean, and the autonomous cities of Ceuta and Melilla in mainland Africa. Peninsular Spain borders France, Andorra, and the Bay of Biscay to the north; the Mediterranean Sea, Gibraltar, and Morocco to the east and south; and Portugal and the Atlantic Ocean to the west. It contains the southernmost point of continental Europe.",
  "spanish guinea": "Spanish Guinea, known in Spanish as Guinea Española, was a set of insular and continental territories controlled by Spain in the Gulf of Guinea and on the Bight of Bonny, in Central Africa. Spain held the territories from 1778 onward. They lay along the coast and islands of the equatorial African region. The colony brought together separate mainland and island possessions under a single administration. It gained independence in 1968 as Equatorial Guinea.",
  "spratly is.": "The Spratly Islands are a disputed archipelago in the South China Sea. Composed of islands, islets, cays, and more than a hundred reefs, sometimes grouped in submerged old atolls, they lie off the coasts of the Philippines, Malaysia, and southern Vietnam. The archipelago holds only a very small amount of naturally occurring land spread across a wide expanse of the sea. It was named after the 19th-century British whaling captain Richard Spratly, who sighted Spratly Island in 1843. The islands are a long-running focus of maritime dispute.",
  "sri lanka": "Sri Lanka, officially the Democratic Socialist Republic of Sri Lanka and formerly known as Ceylon, is an island country in South Asia. It lies in the Indian Ocean, southwest of the Bay of Bengal, and is separated from India by the Gulf of Mannar and the Palk Strait. It shares a maritime border with the Maldives to the southwest and India to the northwest, lying across the Bay of Bengal from Bangladesh and Myanmar to the northeast. Its capital is Sri Jayawardenepura Kotte, while Colombo is its largest city and its political, financial, and cultural centre. The island lies along Indian Ocean sea routes separating it from its neighbours.",
  "st-barthélemy": "Saint Barthélemy, officially the Territorial Collectivity of Saint Barthélemy and also known as St. Barts or St. Barth, is an overseas collectivity of France in the Caribbean. The island lies about 30 kilometres southeast of Saint Martin, northeast of the Dutch islands of Saba and Sint Eustatius, and north of Saint Kitts and Nevis. For many years it was a French commune forming part of Guadeloupe, an overseas region and department of France. In 2003 the island voted in favour of secession from Guadeloupe to form a separate overseas collectivity of France. It has long been associated with French Caribbean administration.",
  "st-martin": "Saint-Martin is the French territory occupying the northern portion of the Caribbean island of Saint Martin, which it shares with the Dutch territory of Sint Maarten to the south under a division dating to a 1648 partition. Its principal town and administrative centre is Marigot, and it lies in the northern Lesser Antilles, separated from Anguilla by the Anguilla Channel. For most of the twentieth century the French side was administered as a commune within the overseas department of Guadeloupe, making it fully part of France and, later, of the European Union. Following a local vote to separate from Guadeloupe, it became a distinct French overseas collectivity in 2007, governed by its own elected Territorial Council. As part of France it confers French and EU citizenship, and its economy rests heavily on tourism.",
  "st. kitts and nevis": "Saint Kitts and Nevis, officially the Federation of Saint Christopher and Nevis, is an island country in the Caribbean consisting of the two islands of Saint Kitts and Nevis. It lies in the Leeward Islands chain of the Lesser Antilles. It is the smallest sovereign state in the Western Hemisphere in both area and population, as well as the world's smallest sovereign federation. The country is a Commonwealth realm, with the British monarch as head of state. Its capital, Basseterre, lies on the larger island of Saint Kitts and serves as the main port for passenger and cargo traffic.",
  "st. pierre and miquelon": "Saint Pierre and Miquelon is a self-governing territorial overseas collectivity of France in the northwestern Atlantic Ocean. It lies off the coast of the Canadian island of Newfoundland and forms an archipelago of eight islands. Its residents are French citizens who elect their own deputy to the National Assembly and take part in senatorial and presidential elections. The territory is an overseas country and territory of the European Union, though not an integral part of it. It is officially known as the Territorial Collectivity of Saint Pierre and Miquelon.",
  "st. vin. and gren.": "Saint Vincent and the Grenadines, sometimes known simply as Saint Vincent, is an archipelagic country in the eastern Caribbean. It lies in the southeast Windward Islands of the Lesser Antilles, at the southern end of the boundary between the Caribbean Sea and the Atlantic Ocean. Saint Lucia lies to its north, Barbados to the east, and Grenada to the south. Most of its territory consists of the main island of Saint Vincent, which includes the capital and largest city, Kingstown. To the south stretch the northern islands of the Grenadines, a chain of smaller islands shared with Grenada.",
  "sudan": "Sudan, officially the Republic of the Sudan, is a country in Northeast Africa and one of the largest states on the continent by area. It borders the Central African Republic, Chad, Libya, Egypt, the Red Sea, Eritrea, Ethiopia, and South Sudan. Its capital and most populous city is Khartoum. The region has been inhabited since deep prehistory, with early cultures such as the Khormusan among its ancient inhabitants. It ranks as Africa's third-largest country by area.",
  "sultanate of utetera": "The Sultanate of Utetera, also referred to as Tippu Tip's state, was a short-lived Arab sultanate established in eastern Africa in the nineteenth century. It was ruled by the Swahili slave trader Tippu Tip, born Hamad al Murjebi, and later by his son Sefu. Its capital was the town of Kasongo, located in what is now Maniema Province in the Democratic Republic of the Congo. At its height the state's controlled territory extended as far as eastern Kasai in one direction and the Aruwimi Basin in the other. It existed only briefly during the late nineteenth century.",
  "suriname": "Suriname, officially the Republic of Suriname, is a country in northern South America that is also considered part of the Caribbean and the West Indies. Situated slightly north of the equator, the vast majority of its territory is covered by rainforest, giving it one of the highest proportions of forest cover in the world. It is bordered by the Atlantic Ocean to the north, French Guiana to the east, Brazil to the south, and Guyana to the west. It is the smallest country in South America by both population and land area. Its capital and largest city is Paramaribo, which is home to roughly half of the population.",
  "swaziland": "Eswatini, formally the Kingdom of Eswatini and historically known as Swaziland, is a landlocked country in Southern Africa. It is bordered by South Africa on all sides except the east, where it shares a border with Mozambique. It is one of the smallest countries in Africa, measuring only a short distance from north to south and from east to west. Despite its small size, its climate and topography are diverse, ranging from a cool, mountainous highveld to a hot, dry lowveld. The executive capital and largest city is Mbabane, while Lobamba serves as the legislative and second capital.",
  "sweden": "Sweden, formally the Kingdom of Sweden, is a Nordic country located on the Scandinavian Peninsula in Northern Europe. It borders Norway to the west and north and Finland to the east, and shares a maritime border with Denmark to the south. It is the largest and most populous of the Nordic countries and one of the larger states in Europe. Its capital and largest city is Stockholm. The great majority of Swedes live in urban areas, concentrated mostly in the southern and central portions of the country.",
  "sweden–norway": "Sweden and Norway, officially the United Kingdoms of Sweden and Norway, was a personal union of the two separate kingdoms under a common monarch and a common foreign policy. It lasted from 1814 until its peaceful dissolution in 1905. The two states retained separate constitutions, laws, legislatures, administrations, state churches, armed forces, and currencies. The kings mostly resided in Stockholm, where foreign diplomatic representations were located. The Norwegian government was presided over by viceroys until that office was left vacant and then abolished in 1873.",
  "switzerland": "Switzerland, officially the Swiss Confederation, is a landlocked country located at the intersection of Central, Western, and Southern Europe. It is bordered by Germany to the north, France to the west, Austria and Liechtenstein to the east, and Italy to the south. The country is divided geographically among the Swiss Alps, the Swiss Plateau, and the Jura Mountains, with the Alps covering most of its territory. Most of the population is concentrated on the plateau, which hosts many of the largest cities and economic centres, including Zurich, Geneva, Basel, Bern, Lausanne, and Lucerne. Switzerland is a federal republic composed of twenty-six cantons, with Bern serving as the federal city and seat of the national government.",
  "syria": "Syria, officially the Syrian Arab Republic, is a country in West Asia located in the Eastern Mediterranean and the Levant. It borders the Mediterranean Sea to the west, Turkey to the north and northwest, Iraq to the east and southeast, Jordan to the south, and Israel and Lebanon to the southwest. It is a republic and is divided administratively into fourteen governorates. Damascus is its capital and largest city. It lies within the Eastern Mediterranean region of the Levant.",
  "são tomé and principe": "São Tomé and Príncipe, officially the Democratic Republic of São Tomé and Príncipe, is an island country in the Gulf of Guinea, off the western equatorial coast of Central Africa. It consists of two archipelagos around the two main islands of São Tomé and Príncipe, which lie a short distance apart and off the northwestern coast of Gabon. It is among the smallest and least populous sovereign states in Africa. The islands were uninhabited until Portuguese explorers, including João de Santarém and Pedro Escobar, reached them in 1470. Those explorers were the first to discover the islands.",
  "taiwan": "Taiwan, officially the Republic of China, is a country in East Asia. The main island, also known as Formosa, lies between the East and South China Seas in the northwestern Pacific Ocean, with mainland China to the northwest, Japan to the northeast, and the Philippines to the south. Mountain ranges dominate the eastern two-thirds of the island, while plains in the western third hold most of its highly urbanized population. The territories under its control also include numerous smaller outlying islands. The largest metropolitan area is formed by the capital Taipei together with New Taipei City and Keelung.",
  "tajikistan": "Tajikistan, officially the Republic of Tajikistan, is a landlocked country in Central Asia. Dushanbe is its capital and most populous city. It borders Afghanistan to the south, Uzbekistan to the west, Kyrgyzstan to the north, and China to the east, and is narrowly separated from Pakistan by Afghanistan's Wakhan Corridor. Its mountainous territory was home in antiquity to cultures of the Neolithic and the Bronze Age, including the Oxus civilisation in the west. Those early cultures make the region one of long-settled human habitation.",
  "tanzania": "Tanzania, officially the United Republic of Tanzania, is a country in East Africa within the African Great Lakes region. It is bordered by Uganda, Kenya, the Indian Ocean, Mozambique, Malawi, Zambia, Rwanda, Burundi, and the Democratic Republic of the Congo. It is the most populous African country located entirely south of the equator. Many important hominid fossils have been found within its borders, making it significant to the study of human origins. Its geography ranges from the Indian Ocean coast to the great lakes and highlands of the interior.",
  "teke": "The Teke Kingdom, also known as the Kingdom of Tio or the Anziku Kingdom, was a Central African state of the Teke (Tio or Bateke) people on the grassland plateaus north of the lower Congo River, spanning parts of present-day Congo-Brazzaville, Gabon, and the Democratic Republic of the Congo. Traditionally dated to around the fourteenth century, it was one of the older states of the region and for a time rivalled the Kingdom of Kongo to its south. It was headed by a king known as the Makoko, whose authority was bound up with control of the powerful nature spirit Nkwe Mbali and who ruled through a hierarchy of tributary lords. Its centres on the Mbé plateau and at Pool Malebo on the Congo River commanded important trade routes, exchanging local goods and later ivory and captives for European wares such as cloth, muskets, and gunpowder. In 1880 its ruler signed a treaty with the French explorer Pierre Savorgnan de Brazza that placed the kingdom under French protection and opened the region to colonization, though the Teke monarchy endures as a traditional institution.",
  "thailand": "Thailand, officially the Kingdom of Thailand and formerly known as Siam until 1939, is a country in Mainland Southeast Asia. It shares land borders with Myanmar to the west and northwest, Laos to the east and northeast, Cambodia to the southeast, and Malaysia to the south. Its coasts front the Gulf of Thailand and the Andaman Sea, giving it maritime boundaries with neighbours including Vietnam, Indonesia, and India. The capital and largest city is Bangkok, the country's dominant political, economic, and cultural center. It occupies a central position in Mainland Southeast Asia, bordered by several neighbouring states on land and by two seas along its coasts.",
  "timor-leste": "Timor-Leste, also known as East Timor and officially the Democratic Republic of Timor-Leste, is a country in Southeast Asia. It comprises the eastern half of the island of Timor, the coastal exclave of Oecusse in the island's northwest, and the islands of Atauro and Jaco. It shares a land border with Indonesia to the west, while Australia lies to the south across the Timor Sea. Dili, on the north coast of Timor, is its capital and largest city. Timor was settled over time by various Papuan and Austronesian peoples, producing a diverse mix of cultures and languages linked to both Southeast Asia and Melanesia.",
  "togo": "Togo, officially the Togolese Republic, is a country in West Africa. It is bordered by Ghana to the west, Benin to the east, and Burkina Faso to the north. The country extends northward from the Gulf of Guinea, where its capital and largest city, Lomé, is located, up to the Burkina Faso border. It is a small, tropical nation with a coastline on the Gulf of Guinea in the south. Togo is often counted among the least developed countries in the world.",
  "tonga": "Tonga, officially the Kingdom of Tonga, is an island country in Polynesia, within the wider region of Oceania. The country consists of 171 islands, of which 45 are inhabited, scattered across a broad expanse of the southern Pacific Ocean. Its islands stretch roughly 800 kilometres from north to south. Most of the population lives on the main island of Tongatapu, the site of the capital. The islands are spread widely across the southern Pacific, with the great majority of people concentrated on that one main island.",
  "transvaal": "Transvaal is a historical geographic term for the land north of, or beyond, the Vaal River in South Africa. A number of states and administrative divisions have carried the name over time. The South African Republic, a Boer republic also known in English as the Transvaal, existed from 1856 until 1902. It was succeeded by the Transvaal Colony under British rule from 1902 to 1910. From 1910 to 1994 the Transvaal was a province, first of the Union of South Africa and later of the Republic of South Africa.",
  "trinidad and tobago": "Trinidad and Tobago, officially the Republic of Trinidad and Tobago, is the southernmost archipelagic country in the Caribbean. It comprises the main islands of Trinidad and Tobago along with several smaller islets, forming the southern end of the Caribbean's eastern island chain. The capital is Port of Spain, while its largest and most populous municipality is Chaguanas. The country lies just off the northeastern coast of Venezuela, close to the South American mainland and northwest of Guyana. Grenada lies to its north and Barbados to its northeast across the surrounding waters.",
  "trucial oman": "The Trucial States, also known as the Trucial Coast, the Trucial Sheikhdoms, or Trucial Oman, were a group of tribal confederations in southeastern Arabia south of the Persian Gulf. Their leaders signed a series of protective treaties with the British Empire between 1820 and 1892, giving the region its name. The states remained an informal British protectorate until the treaties were revoked on 1 December 1971. The following day, six of the sheikhdoms—Dubai, Abu Dhabi, Sharjah, Ajman, Umm Al Quwain, and Fujairah—joined to form the United Arab Emirates. The seventh, Ras Al Khaimah, joined the union on 10 February 1972.",
  "tunisia": "Tunisia, officially the Republic of Tunisia, is a country in the Maghreb region of North Africa. It is bordered by Algeria to the west and southwest, Libya to the southeast, and the Mediterranean Sea to the north and east. Across the sea it shares maritime borders with Italy and Malta to the north and east. The country is home to major historical sites, including the archaeological remains of ancient Carthage and the Great Mosque of Kairouan. It is widely known for its ancient architecture, its souks, and its blue Mediterranean coastline.",
  "turkey": "Turkey, officially the Republic of Türkiye, is a country located mainly in Anatolia in West Asia, with a smaller part called East Thrace in Southeast Europe. It borders the Black Sea to the north; Georgia, Armenia, Azerbaijan, and Iran to the east; Iraq, Syria, and the Mediterranean Sea to the south; and the Aegean Sea, Greece, and Bulgaria to the west. Its population is predominantly ethnic Turks, with Kurds forming the largest ethnic minority. Officially a secular state, Turkey has a Muslim-majority population. Ankara serves as its capital and second-largest city.",
  "turkmenistan": "Turkmenistan is a landlocked country in Central Asia, bordered by Kazakhstan and Uzbekistan to the north, Afghanistan to the southeast, Iran to the south and southwest, and the Caspian Sea to the west. It is one of six independent Turkic states and lies among the most sparsely populated nations of the Asian continent. Ashgabat is its capital and largest city. It has the lowest population of the Central Asian republics, being one of the most sparsely settled countries on the continent. Turkmenistan has long served as a thoroughfare for numerous empires and cultures crossing Central Asia.",
  "turks and caicos is.": "The Turks and Caicos Islands are a British Overseas Territory consisting of the larger Caicos Islands and the smaller Turks Islands. These two groups of tropical islands lie within the Lucayan Archipelago of the Atlantic Ocean and the northern West Indies. The territory is known primarily for tourism and as an offshore financial centre. The islands sit southeast of Mayaguana in the Bahamas island chain and north of the island of Hispaniola. They are among the more prominent of the British overseas territories in the Caribbean region.",
  "tuvalu": "Tuvalu is an archipelagic country in the Polynesian sub-region of Oceania in the Pacific Ocean, lying roughly midway between Hawaii and Australia. It sits east-northeast of the Santa Cruz Islands, northeast of Vanuatu, southeast of Nauru, south of Kiribati, and north of Fiji. The country is composed of three reef islands and six atolls, spread between about 5° and 10° south latitude and 176° and 180° longitude. Its islands lie just west of the International Date Line. Tuvalu is one of the world's smallest and least populous nations, known for its low-lying coral islands.",
  "u.s. virgin is.": "The United States Virgin Islands, officially the Virgin Islands of the United States, are a Caribbean unincorporated territory of the United States. The islands are geographically part of the Virgin Islands archipelago and are located in the Leeward Islands of the Lesser Antilles. They consist of the main islands of Saint Croix, Saint John, and Saint Thomas, along with dozens of surrounding minor islands and cays. The territory has a tropical climate and a landscape shaped by its position in the eastern Caribbean. It remains under United States sovereignty as one of several American territories in the region.",
  "uganda": "Uganda, officially the Republic of Uganda, is a landlocked country in East Africa. It is bordered by Kenya to the east, South Sudan to the north, the Democratic Republic of the Congo to the west, Rwanda to the south-west, and Tanzania to the south. Its southern part includes a substantial portion of Lake Victoria, which it shares with Kenya and Tanzania. Uganda lies within the African Great Lakes region and the Nile basin, and it has a varied equatorial climate. Its capital and largest city is Kampala.",
  "ukraine": "Ukraine is a country in Eastern Europe and is the second-largest country in Europe after Russia. It borders Russia to the east and northeast, Belarus to the north, Poland and Slovakia to the west, and Hungary, Romania and Moldova to the southwest. To the south and southeast it faces the Black Sea and the Sea of Azov. Kyiv is its capital and largest city, followed by Kharkiv, Odesa and Dnipro. The official language of the country is Ukrainian.",
  "united arab emirates": "The United Arab Emirates, also known simply as the Emirates, is a country in West Asia, situated at the eastern end of the Arabian Peninsula. It is a federal semi-constitutional monarchy made up of seven emirates. Abu Dhabi serves as its national capital. The UAE borders Oman to the east and northeast and Saudi Arabia to the southwest. It shares maritime borders with Qatar and Iran in the Persian Gulf and with Oman in the Gulf of Oman.",
  "united kingdom": "The United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland, commonly known as the United Kingdom or Britain, is a country in northwestern Europe, off the coast of the continental mainland. It comprises England, Scotland, Wales and Northern Ireland. The UK includes the island of Great Britain, the north-eastern part of the island of Ireland, and most of the smaller islands within the British Isles. It shares a land border with the Republic of Ireland and is surrounded by the Atlantic Ocean, the North Sea, the English Channel, the Celtic Sea and the Irish Sea. It also maintains sovereignty over the Crown Dependencies and the British Overseas Territories.",
  "united kingdom of great britain and ireland": "The United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland was established by the Acts of Union in 1801, which united the Kingdom of Great Britain and the Kingdom of Ireland into one unitary and sovereign state. It continued in this form until it evolved into the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland, after the Irish Free State gained a degree of independence in 1922. Rapid industrialisation that had begun in the decades prior to the state's formation continued up to the mid-19th century. The Great Irish Famine, exacerbated by government inaction, led to demographic collapse in much of Ireland and increased calls for Irish land reform. During this era of the Industrial Revolution and the growth of trade and finance, Britain largely dominated the world economy.",
  "united states of america": "The United States of America, also known as the United States or America, is a country primarily located in North America. It is a federal republic consisting of 50 states and a federal capital district, Washington, D.C. The 48 contiguous states border Canada to the north and Mexico to the south, with the semi-exclave of Alaska in the northwest and the archipelago of Hawaii in the Pacific Ocean. The United States also asserts sovereignty over five major island territories and various uninhabited islands in Oceania and the Caribbean. It is a megadiverse country with one of the world's largest land areas.",
  "united states virgin islands": "The United States Virgin Islands, officially the Virgin Islands of the United States, are a Caribbean unincorporated territory of the United States. They are geographically part of the Virgin Islands archipelago. The islands are located in the Leeward Islands of the Lesser Antilles. They have a tropical climate. The territory consists of the main islands of Saint Croix, Saint John and Saint Thomas, along with 50 other surrounding minor islands and cays.",
  "uruguay": "Uruguay, officially the Oriental Republic of Uruguay, is a country in South America. It shares borders with Argentina to its west and southwest and Brazil to its north and northeast. It also borders the Río de la Plata to the south and the Atlantic Ocean to the southeast. It is part of the Southern Cone region of South America. Its capital and largest city is Montevideo.",
  "usnb guantanamo bay": "Guantanamo Bay Naval Base, officially known as Naval Station Guantanamo Bay and commonly called GTMO or Gitmo, is a United States military base on the shore of Guantánamo Bay at the southeastern end of Cuba. It occupies land and water leased from Cuba and has functioned under de facto U.S. control since 1903, when it began as a coaling station and naval base. It is the oldest overseas American naval base. Under the lease arrangement, the United States pays the Cuban government an annual sum for use of the bay. The terms of the lease were revised in 1934 to be tied to the value of gold.",
  "uzbekistan": "Uzbekistan, officially the Republic of Uzbekistan, is a doubly landlocked country located in Central Asia. It is bordered by Kazakhstan to the north, Kyrgyzstan to the northeast, Tajikistan to the southeast, Afghanistan to the south, and Turkmenistan to the southwest. It is one of only two doubly landlocked countries in the world, the other being Liechtenstein. It is the most populous of the Central Asian republics. Uzbekistan is a member of the Organization of Turkic States.",
  "vanuatu": "Vanuatu, officially the Republic of Vanuatu, is an archipelagic country in Melanesia located in the South Pacific Ocean. The archipelago is of volcanic origin and lies east of northern Australia, northeast of New Caledonia, east of New Guinea, southeast of the Solomon Islands, and west of Fiji. It was first inhabited by Melanesian people. The first Europeans to visit the islands were a Spanish expedition led by the Portuguese navigator Fernandes de Queirós. They arrived on the largest island, Espíritu Santo, in 1606.",
  "vatican": "Vatican City is an independent city-state located entirely within the Italian capital of Rome, serving as the spiritual and administrative center of the Catholic Church. It came into being as a sovereign state through the Lateran Treaty of 1929, which resolved the long-standing dispute between the Holy See and Italy over the former Papal States. It is the world's smallest fully independent country by both area and population, encompassing landmarks such as St. Peter's Basilica, the Apostolic Palace, and the Vatican Museums. Governed as an absolute elective monarchy, it is headed by the pope, who serves as head of state by virtue of his role as Bishop of Rome and leader of the worldwide Catholic Church. It maintains its own institutions, including a postal service, media outlets, and the Swiss Guard, and enjoys a status distinct from the surrounding Italian state.",
  "venezuela": "Venezuela, officially the Bolivarian Republic of Venezuela, is a country on the northern coast of South America. It consists of a continental landmass and various islands and islets in the Caribbean Sea. Its capital and largest urban agglomeration is Caracas. The continental territory is bordered on the north by the Caribbean Sea and the Atlantic Ocean, on the west by Colombia, on the south by Brazil, to the north-east by Trinidad and Tobago, and on the east by Guyana. Venezuela consists of 23 states, the Capital District, and federal dependencies covering its offshore islands.",
  "vietnam": "Vietnam, officially the Socialist Republic of Viet Nam, is a country at the eastern edge of Mainland Southeast Asia. It is one of two communist states in Southeast Asia and is bordered by China to the north and Laos and Cambodia to the west. It lies along the Gulf of Thailand to the southwest and the South China Sea to the east, where it has shared and disputed maritime borders with other countries. Its capital is Hanoi, while its largest city is Ho Chi Minh City. Vietnam was inhabited by the Paleolithic age, with states established in the first millennium BC on the Red River Delta in modern-day northern Vietnam.",
  "w. sahara": "Western Sahara is a territory in north-western Africa, designated by the United Nations as a non-self-governing territory. It consists mainly of desert flatlands and is one of the most sparsely populated territories in the world. It is often described as Africa's last colony, being the last African territory yet to achieve full independence. Spain colonized the region as the Spanish Sahara, holding it until 1975, when it withdrew during the Spanish transition to democracy. Its final political status has remained unresolved since that withdrawal.",
  "wallis and futuna is.": "Wallis and Futuna, officially the Territory of the Wallis and Futuna Islands, is a French island collectivity in the South Pacific. It lies between Tuvalu to the northwest, Fiji to the southwest, Tonga to the southeast, Samoa to the east, and Tokelau to the northeast. Its capital and largest settlement is Mata Utu. As a French overseas country and territory, it is associated with the European Union rather than being a full member. The territory comprises two main island groups, Wallis and the Futuna Islands, and is among the smallest of France's overseas holdings.",
  "wallis and futuna islands": "Wallis and Futuna, officially the Territory of the Wallis and Futuna Islands, is a French island collectivity in the South Pacific. It lies between Tuvalu to the northwest, Fiji to the southwest, Tonga to the southeast, Samoa to the east, and Tokelau to the northeast. Its capital and largest settlement is Mata Utu. As a French overseas country and territory, it is associated with the European Union rather than being a full member. The territory comprises two main island groups, Wallis and the Futuna Islands, and is among the smallest of France's overseas holdings.",
  "yaka": "The Yaka were a Central African kingdom and people of the Kwango region, in the forest and savanna between the Kwango and Wamba rivers in what is now southwestern Democratic Republic of the Congo, near the Angolan border. The kingdom arose from a westward Lunda migration that established authority over the area, blending with the resident Kongo-related populations so that the Yaka came to speak a Kongo language while retaining Lunda political traditions. It was headed by a paramount chief known as the kiambvu, beneath whom a body of titled nobles and local earth-chiefs governed clusters of villages. The Yaka were a matrilineal, farming and hunting society, and their kingdom was regarded as one of the more centralized and organized states of the region. During the colonial era the Yaka became known for their sustained resistance to European penetration, and they remain celebrated for their sculpture, masks, and other arts.",
  "yeke": "The Yeke Kingdom, also called the Garanganze kingdom, was a nineteenth-century state in the Katanga region of what is now the southeastern Democratic Republic of the Congo. It was founded and ruled by Msiri, a Nyamwezi trader from the Tabora area of present-day Tanzania, and lasted from around 1856 until 1891 under his sole reign. The kingdom grew powerful by exploiting Katanga's copper and ivory, which Msiri traded for firearms and gunpowder, and by controlling a major east-west trans-continental trade route as well as forging alliances through marriage. At its height it dominated a large territory in south-central Africa, extracting wealth from copper, ivory, and the slave trade. The kingdom ended in 1891 when Msiri was killed during the Stairs Expedition, and its lands were absorbed into King Leopold II's Congo Free State.",
  "yemen": "Yemen, officially the Republic of Yemen, is a country in West Asia occupying the southern part of the Arabian Peninsula. It borders Saudi Arabia to the north and Oman to the northeast, with coastlines along the Arabian Sea, the Gulf of Aden, and the Red Sea, and includes the Socotra Archipelago. Across the Horn of Africa it shares maritime borders with Djibouti, Eritrea, Somaliland, and Somalia. Sanaa is its constitutional capital and largest city. Yemen is one of the larger states of the Arabian Peninsula and has a long coastline commanding strategic access between the Red Sea and the Indian Ocean.",
  "zambia": "Zambia, officially the Republic of Zambia, is a landlocked country in Southern Africa. It borders the Democratic Republic of the Congo to the north, Tanzania to the northeast, Malawi to the east, Mozambique to the southeast, Zimbabwe and Botswana to the south, Namibia to the southwest, and Angola to the west. Its capital and largest city is Lusaka, in the south-central part of the country, and its population is concentrated mainly around Lusaka and the Copperbelt Province in the north, the nation's core economic hubs. The region was originally inhabited by Khoisan peoples before being reshaped by the Bantu expansion. These migrations laid the foundation for the peoples who live in the country today.",
  "zimbabwe": "Zimbabwe, officially the Republic of Zimbabwe, is a landlocked country in Southeast Africa lying between the Zambezi and Limpopo Rivers. It borders South Africa to the south, Botswana to the southwest, Zambia to the north, and Mozambique to the east. Its capital and largest city is Harare, with Bulawayo the second largest. The Shona and Northern Ndebele are the country's largest ethnic groups, and it recognizes numerous official languages, of which English, Shona, and Ndebele are the most widely used. Zimbabwe is a member of the United Nations, the African Union, the Southern African Development Community, and the Common Market for Eastern and Southern Africa.",
  "zululand": "Zululand is a name for the historical homeland of the Zulu people in what is now south-eastern South Africa. It is most closely associated with the Zulu Kingdom, the powerful nineteenth-century state that arose in the region. Under later South African policy the name was applied to KwaZulu, a Bantustan established for Zulu people in the twentieth century. Today the region falls within the province of KwaZulu-Natal, and the name survives in the Zululand District Municipality. It is also used ecclesiastically, as in the Anglican Diocese of Zululand.",
  "åland": "Åland is an autonomous and demilitarised region of Finland, situated in an archipelago at the entrance to the Gulf of Bothnia in the Baltic Sea. It received its autonomy in 1920 and is the smallest of Finland's regions by both area and population. Its sole official language is Swedish, and its capital is Mariehamn. The region comprises Fasta Åland, the main island where the great majority of the population lives, together with thousands of surrounding skerries and smaller islands, only a few dozen of which are inhabited. Fasta Åland is separated from the Roslagen coast of Sweden to the west by a stretch of open water.",
  "british empire": "The British Empire was a global network of colonies, protectorates, dominions, mandates, and other territories ruled or administered by the United Kingdom, originating with English overseas trading posts and settlements from the late 16th and early 17th centuries and enduring until the era of decolonisation in the mid-to-late 20th century. At its height in the early 20th century it was the largest empire in history, spanning every inhabited continent and including major possessions in North America, the Caribbean, Africa, South and Southeast Asia, Australasia, and numerous islands across the Atlantic, Indian, and Pacific oceans. Its holdings were governed through varied arrangements, from crown colonies under Crown-appointed governors and protectorates administered through local rulers to self-governing dominions such as Canada, Australia, New Zealand, and South Africa that gained increasing autonomy, formalised by the Statute of Westminster in 1931. The empire's expansion was driven by maritime commerce, naval power, and the pursuit of resources and markets, and it played a central role in global trade, migration, and the spread of the English language, legal traditions, and institutions. Following the Second World War most territories became independent, with many joining the Commonwealth of Nations, and the empire's legacy remains significant and widely debated in the histories of its former colonies and of Britain itself.",
  "french colonial empire": "The French colonial empire was the collection of overseas territories, protectorates, and mandates ruled or administered by France, conventionally divided into a first empire that flourished from the 16th to the 18th centuries and a second empire that expanded through the 19th and early 20th centuries. The first empire centered on North America, the Caribbean, and trading posts in India and West Africa, much of which was lost or ceded by the early 19th century, while the second empire, beginning with the conquest of Algiers in 1830, came to span large parts of Africa, Indochina and other regions of Southeast Asia, and scattered island possessions across the Pacific, Indian, and Atlantic oceans. At its height it ranked among the largest empires in the world, second only to the British Empire, and its holdings were governed through a patchwork of directly ruled colonies, protectorates that retained local rulers, and later League of Nations mandates, all ultimately subordinate to authorities in Paris. Colonial administration blended assimilationist ideals with unequal legal systems, and most colonial subjects were governed as such rather than granted full French citizenship. Following the Second World War the empire was progressively dismantled through decolonization, culminating in the independence of most territories by the 1960s, though France retains several overseas departments and territories, and the empire left enduring legacies in language, law, and the cultural sphere often described as the Francophone world.",
  "german colonial empire": "The German colonial empire was the collection of overseas territories governed by Germany from the mid-1880s until the aftermath of the First World War, established largely under Chancellor Otto von Bismarck as the German Empire joined the late-nineteenth-century scramble for colonies. Its possessions lay chiefly in Africa, including German East Africa, German South West Africa, Kamerun, and Togoland, alongside holdings in the Pacific such as parts of New Guinea, Samoa, and various island groups, and a leased concession at Kiautschou in China. Administration was at first often delegated to chartered trading companies granted state protection, but responsibility increasingly shifted to direct imperial rule overseen by a colonial office answerable to the government in Berlin. German rule was marked by economic exploitation and military campaigns against local populations, including the war against the Herero and Nama peoples in South West Africa, which is widely regarded as a genocide. Following Germany's defeat in the First World War, the empire was dissolved by the Treaty of Versailles in 1919, with its territories redistributed among the victorious powers as League of Nations mandates.",
  "italian colonial empire": "The Italian colonial empire was the overseas territories controlled by Italy from the late nineteenth century until the mid-twentieth century, concentrated mainly in northern and eastern Africa. Its principal possessions were Eritrea, Italian Somaliland, and Libya, joined after the conquest of Ethiopia in the 1930s to form Italian East Africa, while smaller holdings included the Dodecanese Islands in the Aegean and a concession in the Chinese city of Tianjin. The empire was administered through appointed governors and colonial officials answerable to the government in Rome, and its expansion was driven by aspirations to national prestige, strategic access to the Mediterranean and Red Sea, and settlement schemes for Italian emigrants. It reached its greatest extent in the late 1930s but collapsed during the Second World War, when Allied forces occupied its African territories, and Italy formally renounced its colonies in the 1947 peace treaty. Its legacy includes lasting cultural and infrastructural traces in the former colonies, contested historical memory in Italy, and the shaping of the modern states of Libya, Eritrea, Somalia, and Ethiopia.",
  "dutch colonial empire": "The Dutch colonial empire was the network of overseas territories, colonies, and trading posts controlled by the Netherlands from the late 16th century until the late 20th century. At its greatest extent it stretched across the globe, with holdings in the East Indies and other parts of Asia, southern and western Africa, the Caribbean, and northeastern South America, together with trading stations in North America, India, Ceylon, and East Asia. Much of the empire was administered not directly by the state but by chartered trading companies, above all the Dutch East India Company and the Dutch West India Company, which were granted quasi-governmental powers to wage war, sign treaties, and govern territory in pursuit of commerce in spices, sugar, and other goods. After these companies were dissolved around the turn of the 19th century, their possessions passed to the Kingdom of the Netherlands, which ruled the remaining colonies as a state until the independence of Indonesia in 1949 and Suriname in 1975. Its legacy endures in language, place names, legal and administrative institutions, and lasting cultural ties, while several Caribbean islands remain constituent countries within the modern Kingdom of the Netherlands.",
  "portuguese empire": "The Portuguese Empire was one of the earliest and longest-lasting of the European seaborne colonial empires, conventionally dated from the capture of Ceuta in 1415 to the handover of Macau in 1999. Built on maritime exploration and trade, it was a globally dispersed network of coastal territories, fortified ports, and trading posts spanning South America, Africa, the Indian subcontinent, Southeast and East Asia, and Oceania, with Brazil as its largest and most populous colony until Brazilian independence in 1822. Authority was exercised on behalf of the Portuguese crown through appointed governors and viceroys, royal officials, and military garrisons, with ultimate legal and administrative control centered in Lisbon. Its economy rested heavily on the spice and Asian trade, plantation agriculture, and the transatlantic slave trade, and after the loss of Brazil the empire became predominantly African, centered on Angola, Mozambique, and Guinea. The empire's legacy includes the global spread of the Portuguese language, Catholicism, and cultural influence, as well as the enduring political and social consequences of colonization and the slave trade across several continents.",
  "spanish empire": "The Spanish Empire was one of the largest empires in history, extending from the late fifteenth century following the transatlantic voyages of Christopher Columbus until the twentieth century, and at its height it was often described as the empire on which the sun never set. Its territories spanned much of the Americas, the Philippines and other Pacific islands, coastal enclaves and possessions in Africa, and lands within Europe including areas of Italy and the Low Countries. The empire was ruled by the Crown of Castile and administered through institutions such as the Council of the Indies and a network of viceroyalties, notably New Spain and Peru, each governed by a viceroy acting as the monarch's direct representative. Reaching its zenith under the Habsburg dynasty during the sixteenth and seventeenth centuries, it drew great wealth from silver mining and transoceanic trade while spreading the Spanish language, Catholicism, and Iberian institutions across its domains. It declined gradually amid warfare and financial strain, losing most of its American colonies in the early nineteenth century and its remaining major overseas holdings by the end of that century, leaving a lasting legacy in the languages, religions, and cultures of many nations today.",
  "belgian colonial empire": "The Belgian colonial empire comprised the overseas territories governed by Belgium and its monarch, overwhelmingly concentrated in Central Africa and dominated by the vast Congo basin, alongside the smaller neighboring territory of Ruanda-Urundi and a few minor holdings and concessions elsewhere. Its principal possession originated as the Congo Free State, held from the 1880s as the personal domain of King Leopold II, whose regime of forced labor and violent resource extraction provoked international outcry and led the Belgian state to annex the territory as the Belgian Congo in 1908. Ruanda-Urundi, seized from German East Africa during the First World War, was administered by Belgium as a League of Nations mandate and later a United Nations trust territory, governed in close connection with the Congo. Colonial administration rested largely on a partnership of the state, Catholic missions, and private companies, which together controlled government, education, and the extraction of minerals, rubber, and other commodities. The empire was dismantled around 1960 to 1962 as the Congo, Rwanda, and Burundi became independent, and its legacy remains marked by the enduring social and political consequences of Belgian rule and the enormous human toll of the early Congo regime.",
  "danish realm": "The Danish Realm is the collective term for the Kingdom of Denmark together with its North Atlantic dependencies, historically comprising metropolitan Denmark in northern Europe alongside Iceland, Greenland, and the Faroe Islands. Denmark proper occupies the Jutland peninsula and an archipelago between the North and Baltic Seas, while its dependencies stretch far across the North Atlantic and into the Arctic, making Greenland the world's largest island and giving the realm an enormous but sparsely populated overseas reach. The realm has been governed as a unitary constitutional monarchy under the Danish crown, with the outlying territories long administered as dependencies before gradually acquiring autonomy, Iceland gaining home rule in 1904 and full sovereignty under a personal union in 1918 before becoming an independent republic in 1944. The Faroe Islands and Greenland remained within the kingdom and were granted home rule in the 20th century and expanded self-government thereafter, an arrangement known as Rigsfællesskabet, the Unity of the Realm, under which Copenhagen retains foreign affairs and defence. As a historical entity the Danish Realm reflects the maritime and colonial expansion of a small European kingdom into the North Atlantic and Arctic, and its legacy survives in the lasting constitutional ties between Denmark, Greenland, and the Faroe Islands.",
  "warlord-era china": "Warlord-era China refers to the period of the Republic of China, roughly from the death of President Yuan Shikai in 1916 until reunification in 1928, when effective authority over the country was fragmented among rival regional military commanders. Although a central Beiyang government based in Beijing continued to represent China internationally and was recognized by foreign powers as the legitimate state, in practice it controlled little beyond the capital and functioned largely as the instrument of whichever military clique held Beijing at a given time. Real power rested with competing factions such as the Anhui, Zhili, and Fengtian cliques in the north and the Yunnan, Guangxi, and Sichuan cliques in the south, each holding sway over provinces or clusters of provinces through their own armies and shifting alliances. The era was marked by frequent civil wars, a persistent north-south division, weak central institutions, and continued foreign influence over Chinese territory and finances. It ended with the Kuomintang's Northern Expedition, which defeated or absorbed the major warlords and formally reunified China under a Nationalist government at Nanjing in 1928, though regional military power endured well beyond that date.",
  "ussr": "The Soviet Union, officially the Union of Soviet Socialist Republics (USSR), was a state in Eastern Europe and northern Asia that existed from 1922 until its dissolution in 1991, emerging from the Russian Empire in the wake of the Russian Revolution and civil war. Stretching from the Baltic Sea and the borders of Central and Eastern Europe eastward across Siberia to the Pacific Ocean, it was the largest country in the world by land area and spanned numerous time zones and climatic zones. It was organized as a nominally federal union of national republics, growing to encompass fifteen constituent republics, of which the Russian Soviet Federative Socialist Republic was the largest and most dominant. In practice it functioned as a highly centralized one-party state governed by the Communist Party under the ideology of Marxism-Leninism, with a command economy in which industry and agriculture were placed under state control. As one of the two superpowers of the Cold War, it exercised broad influence over allied socialist states and left a lasting legacy on twentieth-century geopolitics, its collapse giving rise to fifteen independent successor states.",
  "empire of japan": "The Empire of Japan was the Japanese state that existed from the Meiji Restoration in 1868 until the promulgation of a new constitution in 1947, spanning the reigns of the Meiji, Taishō, and Shōwa emperors. Centered on the Japanese archipelago in East Asia, it expanded through war and annexation to include Taiwan, Korea, southern Sakhalin, the Kuril Islands, and Pacific island territories, and during the Second World War it briefly occupied large portions of the Asia-Pacific region. Under the Meiji Constitution of 1889 it was governed as a semi-constitutional monarchy in which the emperor was the sovereign head of state and supreme commander of the armed forces, alongside a bicameral Imperial Diet, an appointed cabinet, and influential elder statesmen. From the 1920s and 1930s the military assumed a dominant role in politics, driving an era of aggressive expansionism and colonial rule across the region. The empire ended with Japan's defeat and surrender in 1945 and the subsequent Allied occupation, after which the 1947 constitution reduced the emperor to a ceremonial figure and reconstituted the country as a parliamentary democracy.",
  "union of south africa": "The Union of South Africa was a state occupying the southern tip of the African continent, established in 1910 through the unification of the former Cape, Natal, Transvaal, and Orange River colonies. It began as a self-governing Dominion of the British Empire and later a Commonwealth realm, with the British monarch as head of state represented locally by a Governor-General, while executive power rested with a prime minister and cabinet answerable to an elected parliament. Its territory encompassed the same broad region as present-day South Africa, and it administered the neighbouring mandate of South West Africa, while the surrounding British high commission territories remained separate. Political power was reserved almost entirely for the white minority, with the Black African majority as well as Coloured and Indian communities largely excluded from the franchise, laying the groundwork for the segregationist policies that culminated in apartheid. The Union endured until 1961, when a referendum among white voters led to its replacement by the Republic of South Africa and its departure from the Commonwealth.",
};
